# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tonga
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Between 19 May and 21 October 1883, the volcanic island of Krakatoa (located in the Sunda Strait, then part of the Dutch East Indies—modern-day Indonesia) began erupting, lasting more than five months.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On 27 August, the island had its most significant eruption, which destroyed over 70% of the island and its surrounding archipelago, the island collapsing into a caldera.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruption of 27 August had an estimated volcanic explosivity index of 6, and is one of the deadliest and most destructive volcanic events in recorded history; the third explosion of that day, that occurred at 10:02 a.m., remains the loudest-known sound in history.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The explosion was heard 3,110 kilometres (1,930 mi) away in Perth, Western Australia, and Rodrigues near Mauritius, 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi) away.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The acoustic pressure wave circled the globe more than three times.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At least 36,417 deaths are attributed to the eruption and the tsunamis it created.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Significant additional effects were felt worldwide in the days and weeks after the volcano's eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Additional seismic activity was reported until February 1884, but any reports after October 1883 were dismissed by Rogier Verbeek's subsequent investigation into the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In the years before the 1883 eruption, seismic activity around the Krakatau volcano was intense, with earthquakes felt as far away as the Australian Northern Territory, one of which, in 1880, damaged a lighthouse.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Strombolian activity began on 20 May 1883, and steam venting began to occur regularly from Perboewatan, the northernmost of the island's three cones.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Eruptions of ash reached an estimated altitude of 6 kilometres (20,000 ft), and explosions could be heard in Batavia (Jakarta) 160 km (100 mi) away, rattling windows and doors.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An excursion party sent to the island on 26 May reported that the islands were covered with a fine white dust, with explosions coming from Perboewatan every five to ten minutes.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although by this time the eruptions were calming down, some of the explosions were still very energetic, hurling pumice opposite the direction of the wind.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A large crater approximately 900 metres (3,000 ft) in diameter formed, with a cavity from which issued plumes of steam.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruptions soon quietened after the initial violence.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Around 16 June, there were loud explosions and a thick black cloud covered the islands for five days.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruptions started gaining strength again on 19 June.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On 24 June, a prevailing east wind cleared the cloud, and two ash columns could be seen issuing from Krakatau.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It was also noticed that the summit cone of Perboewatan was gone, which an extensive report of a few years later attributes it to having been blown away.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The seat of the eruption is believed to have been a new vent or vents that formed on that day, between Perboewatan and Danan.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The violence of the ongoing eruptions caused tides in the vicinity to be unusually high, and ships at anchor had to be moored with chains.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Earthquakes were felt at Anyer, Banten, and ships began to report large pumice masses to the west in the Indian Ocean.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A third vent, and later many more, appeared.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruptions continued throughout July, and their violence continued to increase until the explosions of 27 August.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In early August, a Dutch topographical engineer, Captain H.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ferzenaar, investigated the Krakatau islands.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] He noted three major ash columns (the newer from Danan), which obscured the western part of the island, and steam plumes from at least eleven other vents, mostly between Danan and Rakata.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] When he landed, he noted an ash layer about 50 cm (1.6 ft) thick and the destruction of all vegetation, leaving only tree stumps.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] He advised against any further landings.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] By 25 August, the Krakatau eruptions intensified.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At about 1:00 p.m. on 26 August, the eruption entered its climactic phase.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] By 2:00 p.m., a black ash cloud could be seen 27 km (89,000 ft) high.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At this point, the eruption was almost continuous, and explosions could be heard every ten minutes.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] By 5:00 p.m., the explosions were audible all over Java.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Waves approximately a metre high, which may have been produced by steam explosions, began battering the coasts of Java and Sumatra at 5:30 p.m., and continued throughout the night.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ships within 20 km (12 mi) of the volcano reported heavy ash fall, with pieces of hot pumice up to 10 cm (4 in) in diameter landing on their decks.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Between 7:00 and 8:00 p.m., a small tsunami hit the shores of Java and Sumatra, 40 km (25 mi) away.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On 27 August, a series of eleven enormous explosions occurred, which marked the climax of the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At 5:30 a.m., the first explosion was at Perboewatan, triggering a tsunami heading to Telok Betong, now known as Bandar Lampung.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At 6:44 a.m., Krakatau exploded again at Danan, with the resulting tsunami propagating eastward and westward.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The third and largest explosion, at 10:02 a.m.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] (some sources say 9:58 a.m.), was so powerful that it was heard 3,110 km (1,930 mi) away in Perth, Western Australia, and the Indian Ocean island of Rodrigues near Mauritius, 4,800 km (3,000 mi) away, where the blast was thought to have been cannon fire from a nearby ship.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The third explosion was the loudest sound that has ever been measured.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The loudness of the blast heard 160 km (100 mi) from the volcano has been calculated to have been 180 dBSPL (180 dB re 20 μPa, or 20 kPa).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although heard at very great distances, the sounds of the largest explosions were much less noticeable, or not heard at all in close proximity to the volcano.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The reasons for this are complex and still debated by volcanologists today but a possible explanation is that the sound waves may have been projected upwards to the stratosphere and reflected away from the area, in part by ash suspended in the air.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although often directly linked in popular accounts, the explosions and the tsunamis were probably caused by distinct mechanisms.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The explosions may have emanated from huge pulses of gas-laden magma, whilst the waves followed later when the ejecta slumped back down into the surrounding sea.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The worst of the many tsunamis that resulted were estimated to have been over 30 m (100 ft) high in places.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A large area of the Sunda Strait and places on the Sumatran coast were affected by pyroclastic flows from the volcano.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Verbeek and others believe that the final major Krakatau eruption was a lateral blast, or pyroclastic surge.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Material shot out of the volcano at 2,575 km/h (1,600 mph).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The energy released from the explosion has been estimated to be equal to about 200 megatonnes of TNT (840 petajoules), roughly four times as powerful as the Tsar Bomba, the most powerful thermonuclear weapon ever detonated.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This makes it one of the most powerful explosions in recorded history.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At 10:41 a.m., a landslide tore off half of Rakata's cone, along with the remainder of the island to the north of Rakata.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It is still debated whether this event caused the loudest of the explosions but, either way, the collapse of the island into the magma chamber heralded the end of the paroxysmal phase.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Some islands in the western Indian Ocean, approximately 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi) away, still heard it at nearly the same level as a gun blast.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Due to the limitations of the speed of sound, it is likely that people on these far away islands did not hear Krakatau for nearly four hours after its eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The pressure wave generated by the colossal third explosion radiated out from Krakatau at 1,086 km/h (675 mph).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruption is estimated to have reached 180 dBSPL (180 dB re 20 μPa, or 20 kPa), loud enough to be heard 5,000 kilometres (3,100 mi) away.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At Batavia, the air waves burst windows and cracked walls.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The pressure wave was recorded on barographs worldwide.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Several barographs recorded the wave seven times over five days: four times with the wave travelling away from the volcano to its antipodal point and three times travelling back to the volcano.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Hence, the wave rounded the globe three and a half times.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Massive tsunamis struck the coastlines of the Sunda Strait, entirely submerging some islands.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Some 80 km (50 mi) away, the low-lying Thousand Islands were submerged under 2 metres (7 ft) of seawater, forcing people to climb trees.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The tsunamis produced by the third explosion were the largest, although the first two explosions did produce smaller tsunamis.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The town of Merak was destroyed by a tsunami that was 46 metres (151 ft) high.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The waves reached heights of up to 24 metres (79 ft) along the south coast of Sumatra and up to 42 metres (138 ft) along the west coast of Java.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The tsunamis washed the land clean of vegetation and destroyed human settlements.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The *Loudon*, which at the time was anchored near the village of Telok Betong, survived the waves.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Away from the coasts of the Sunda Strait, the waves reached a height of four metres (13 ft) on Southern Sumatra.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ships as far away as South Africa rocked as tsunamis hit them, and the victims' bodies were found floating in the ocean for months after the event.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The tsunamis which accompanied the eruption were believed to have been caused by gigantic pyroclastic flows entering the sea; each of the four great explosions was accompanied by large pyroclastic flows resulting from the gravitational collapse of the eruption columns.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This caused several cubic kilometres of material to enter the sea, displacing an equal volume of seawater.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Smaller waves were recorded on tidal gauges as far away as the English Channel.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] These occurred too soon to be remnants of the initial tsunamis, which owing to a wavelength of less than 7 km (4 mi), failed to cause significant damage at large distance, and may have been caused by concussive air waves from the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] These air waves circled the globe several times and were still detectable on barographs five days later.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] About 10% of the eruption fatalities were from pyroclastic flows.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The pyroclastic flows and surges produced by the third explosion moved faster than 100 km/h (62 mph) and travelled over the sea up to 80 km (50 mi) from the source, affecting an area constrained to a minimum of 4,000 km2 (1,500 sq mi).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Pyroclastic deposits thought to be from the flows have been found on Southeast Sumatra, and northwest of the volcano on the islands of Sebesi, Sebuku and Lagoendi, while on Southwest Sumatra the flows burnt victims.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] They travelled 40 km (25 mi) across the Sunda Strait.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Once they hit Southern Sumatra, they incinerated entire villages and burned all vegetation.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Two thousand of the corpses in Southern Sumatra appear to have been scorched to death, presumably by the pyroclastic flows.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Besse*, around 65 km (40 mi) north-northeast and 80 km (50 mi) east-northeast of Krakatau, respectively, were hit by strong winds and tephra.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] They were farther away than the scorched victims of the hot flows in Sumatra, so the ships and crew survived.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The flows had moved across the water on a cushion of superheated steam.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There are also indications of submarine pyroclastic flows reaching 15 km (9 mi) from the volcano.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An estimated 20 cubic kilometres (4.8 cu mi) of tephra was deposited.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ash was propelled to an estimated height of 80 km (260,000 ft).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It is estimated that as much as 18–21 km3 (4.3–5.0 cu mi) of ignimbrite were deposited over 1.1 million km2 (420,000 sq mi).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Around noon on 27 August 1883, a rain of hot ash fell around Ketimbang (now Kalianda in Lampung Province) in Sumatra, known as 'The Burning Ashes of Ketimbang', killing approximately 1,000 people in Sumatra.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On the regional scale the effects were limited to some land in Banten, approximately 80 km south, never being repopulated and reverting to jungle, which is now the Ujung Kulon National Park.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Huge fields of floating pumice were reported for months after the event.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There are numerous reports of groups of human skeletal remains floating across the Indian Ocean on rafts of volcanic pumice and washing up on the east coast of Africa up to a year after the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An observation made two weeks after the eruption describes the state of the affected areas, where the village of Tjaringin once was.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The official reported death toll was 36,417.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There were no survivors from the 3,000 people on the island of Sebesi.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In the aftermath of the eruption, it was found that Krakatoa had almost entirely disappeared, except for the southern third.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Much of the Rakata cone had been sheared away, leaving behind a 250-metre (820 ft) cliff.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Of the northern two-thirds of the island, only a rocky islet named Bootsmansrots ('Bosun's Rock'), a fragment of Danan, was left; Poolsche Hoed had disappeared.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The huge amount of material the volcano deposited drastically altered the ocean floor.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The huge amount of ignimbrite deposits largely filled the 30–40-metre-deep (100–130 ft) basin around the mountain.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The land masses of Verlaten and Lang islands were increased, as was the western part of the remnant of Rakata.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Much of this gained material quickly eroded, but volcanic ash remains a significant part of the geological composition of these islands.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Two nearby sandbanks (called Steers and Calmeyer after the two naval officers who investigated them) were built up into islands by ashfall, but the sea later washed them away.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Seawater on hot volcanic deposits on Steers and Calmeyer had caused steam to rise, which some mistook for a continued eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In the year following the eruption, average Northern Hemisphere summer temperatures fell by 0.4 °C (0.72 °F).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The record rainfall that hit Southern California during the water year from July 1883 to June 1884—Los Angeles received 970 millimetres (38.18 in) and San Diego 660 millimetres (25.97 in)—has been attributed to the Krakatoa eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There was no El Niño during that period as is usual when heavy rain occurs in Southern California, but many scientists doubt that there was a causal relationship.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruption injected a tremendous amount of sulfur dioxide (SO2) gas high into the stratosphere, which was subsequently transported by high-level winds all over the planet.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This led to a global increase in sulfuric acid (H2SO4) concentration in high-level cirrus clouds.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The resulting increase in cloud reflectivity (or albedo) reflected more incoming light from the sun than usual and cooled the entire planet until the sulfur fell to the ground as acid rain.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The 1883 Krakatoa eruption darkened the sky worldwide for years afterwards and produced spectacular sunsets worldwide for many months.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] British artist William Ascroft made thousands of colour sketches of the red sunsets halfway around the world from Krakatoa in the years after the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The ash caused "such vivid red sunsets that fire engines were called out in New York, Poughkeepsie and New Haven to quench the apparent conflagration".
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This eruption also produced a Bishop's Ring around the sun by day, and a volcanic purple light at twilight.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In 2004, an astronomer proposed the idea that the red sky shown in Edvard Munch's 1893 painting *The Scream* is an accurate depiction of the sky over Norway after the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Weather watchers of the time tracked and mapped the effects on the sky.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] They labelled the phenomenon the "equatorial smoke stream".
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This was the first identification of what is known today as the jet stream.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] For several years following the eruption, it was reported that the moon appeared to be blue and sometimes green.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This was because some ash clouds were filled with particles about 1 μm wide—the right size to strongly scatter red light while allowing other colours to pass.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] White moonbeams shining through the clouds emerged blue and sometimes green.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] People also saw lavender suns and, for the first time, recorded noctilucent clouds.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although the violent phase of the 1883 eruption was over by the late afternoon of 27 August, after light returned by 29 August, reports continued for months that Krakatoa was still in eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Verbeek's committee's earliest duties were to determine if this was true and verify reports of other volcanoes erupting on Java and Sumatra.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In general, these were found to be false.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Small eruptions, mostly of mud, continued into October 1883.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Verbeek discounted any claims of Krakatoa still erupting after mid-October due to steaming of hot material, landslides due to heavy monsoon rains that season, and "hallucinations due to electrical activity" seen from a distance.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] No signs of further activity were seen until 1913 when an eruption was reported.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An investigation could find no evidence the volcano was awakening.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It was determined that what had been mistaken for renewed activity had been a major landslide (possibly the one which formed the second arc to Rakata's cliff).
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Examinations after 1930 of bathymetric charts made in 1919 show evidence of a bulge indicative of magma near the surface at the site that became Anak Krakatoa.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The fate of northern Krakatoa has been the subject of some dispute among geologists.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It was initially proposed that the island had been blown apart by the force of the eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Most of the material deposited by the volcano is magmatic in origin, and the caldera formed by the eruption is not extensively filled with deposits from the 1883 eruption.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This indicates that the island subsided into an empty magma chamber at the end of the eruption sequence rather than having been destroyed during the eruptions.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Based on the findings of contemporary investigators, the established hypotheses assume that part of the island subsided before the first explosions on the morning of 27 August.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Geological evidence does not support the assumption that only subsidence before the explosion was the cause.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] For instance, the pumice and ignimbrite deposits are not of a kind consistent with a magma-seawater interaction.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A numerical model for a Krakatoa hydrovolcanic explosion and the resulting tsunami was described by Mader & Gittings, in 2006.
[src:tonga/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A high wall of water is formed that is initially higher than 100 metres driven by the shocked water, basalt and air.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The **1918–1920 flu pandemic**, also known as the **Great Influenza epidemic** or by the misleading name **Spanish flu**, was an exceptionally deadly global influenza pandemic caused by the H1N1 subtype of the influenza A virus.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The earliest probable cases were documented in March 1918 in Haskell County, Kansas, United States, with further cases recorded in France, Germany and the United Kingdom in April.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Two years later, nearly a third of the global population, or an estimated 500 million people, had been infected.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Estimates of deaths range from 17 million to 50 million, and possibly as high as 100 million, making it one of the deadliest pandemics in history.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Limited historical epidemiological data make the pandemic's geographic origin indeterminate, with competing hypotheses on the initial spread.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Most influenza outbreaks disproportionately kill the young and old, but this pandemic had unusually high mortality for young adults.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Scientists offer several explanations for the high mortality, including a six-year climate anomaly affecting migration of disease vectors with increased likelihood of spread through bodies of water.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, the claim that young adults had a high mortality during the pandemic has been contested.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] World War I exacerbated malnourishment, overcrowding in medical camps and hospitals, and poor hygiene which in turn promoted bacterial superinfection, killing most of the victims after a typically prolonged death bed.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This pandemic was known by many different names depending on place, time, and context.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The etymology of alternative names historicises the scourge and its effects on people who would only learn years later that viruses caused influenza.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Outbreaks of influenza-like illness were documented in 1916–17 at British military hospitals in Étaples, France, and just across the English Channel at Aldershot, England.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Clinical indications in common with the 1918 pandemic included rapid symptom progression to a "dusky" heliotrope face.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This characteristic blue-violet cyanosis in expiring patients led to the name 'purple death'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In 1918, 'epidemic influenza', also known at the time as 'the grip' (French: *la grippe*, grasp), appeared in Kansas, U.S., during late spring, and early reports from Spain began appearing on 21 May.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Reports from both places called it 'three-day fever'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Many alternative names are exonyms in the practice of making new infectious diseases seem foreign.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This pattern was observed even before the 1889–1890 pandemic, also known as the 'Russian flu', when the Russians already called epidemic influenza the 'Chinese catarrh', the Germans called it the 'Russian pest', and the Italians called it the 'German disease'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] These epithets were re-used in the 1918 pandemic, along with new ones.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Outside Spain, the disease was soon misnamed 'Spanish influenza'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In a 2 June 1918 *The Times* of London dispatch titled, "The Spanish Epidemic," a correspondent in Madrid reported over 100,000 victims of, "The unknown disease...clearly of a gripal character," without referring to "Spanish influenza" directly.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Three weeks later *The Times* reported that, "Everybody thinks of it as the 'Spanish' influenza to-day." Three days after that an advertisement appeared in *The Times* for Formamint tablets to prevent "Spanish influenza".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] When it reached Moscow, *Pravda* announced, "*Ispánka* (the Spanish lady) is in town," making 'the Spanish lady' another common name.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The outbreak did not originate in Spain, but reporting did, due to wartime censorship in belligerent nations.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Spain was a neutral country unconcerned with appearances of combat readiness, and without a wartime propaganda machine to prop up morale, so its newspapers freely reported epidemic effects, making Spain the apparent locus of the epidemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The censorship was so effective that Spain's health officials were unaware its neighboring countries were similarly affected.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In an October 1918 "Madrid Letter" to the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, a Spanish official protested, "we were surprised to learn that the disease was making ravages in other countries, and that people there were calling it the 'Spanish grip'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] French press initially used 'American flu', but adopted 'Spanish flu' in lieu of antagonizing an ally.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the spring of 1918, British soldiers called it 'Flanders flu', while German soldiers used '*Flandern-Fieber*' (Flemish fever), both after a battlefield in Belgium where many soldiers on both sides fell ill.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Senegal it was named 'Brazilian flu', and in Brazil, 'German flu'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Spain it was also known as the 'French flu' (*gripe francesa*), or the 'Naples Soldier' (*Soldado de Nápoles*), after a popular song from a zarzuela.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Spanish flu (*gripe española*) is now a common name in Spain, but remains controversial there.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Othering derived from geopolitical borders and social boundaries.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Poland it was the 'Bolshevik disease', while in Russia it was referred to it as the 'Kirghiz disease'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Some Africans called it a 'white man's sickness', but in South Africa, white men also used the ethnophaulism *'kaffersiekte'* (lit.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Japan blamed sumo wrestlers for bringing the disease home from Taiwan, calling it 'sumo flu' (*Sumo Kaze*).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] World Health Organization 'best practices' first published in 2015 now aim to prevent social stigma by not associating culturally significant names with new diseases, listing "Spanish flu" under "examples to be avoided".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Many authors now eschew calling this the Spanish flu, instead using variations of '1918–19/20 flu/influenza pandemic'.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Some language endonyms did not name specific regions or groups of people.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This outbreak was also commonly known as the 'great influenza epidemic', after the 'great war', a common name for World War I before World War II.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] French military doctors originally called it 'disease 11' (*maladie onze*).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] German doctors downplayed the severity by calling it 'pseudo influenza' (Greek: *pseudo*, false), while in Africa, doctors tried to get patients to take it more seriously by calling it 'influenza vera' (Latin: *vera*, true).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A children's song from the 1889–90 flu pandemic was shortened and adapted into a skipping-rope rhyme popular in 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Despite its name, historical and epidemiological data cannot identify the geographic origin of the Spanish flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, several theories have been proposed.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The first confirmed cases originated in the United States.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Crosby stated in 2003 that the flu originated in Kansas, and author John M.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Barry described a January 1918 outbreak in Haskell County, Kansas, as the origin in his 2004 article.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A 2018 study of tissue slides and medical reports led by professor Michael Worobey found evidence against the disease originating from Kansas, as those cases were milder and had fewer deaths compared to the infections in New York City in the same period.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The study did find evidence through phylogenetic analyses that the virus likely had a North American origin, though it was not conclusive.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In addition, the haemagglutinin glycoproteins of the virus suggest that it originated long before 1918, and other studies suggest that the reassortment of the H1N1 virus likely occurred in or around 1915.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The major UK troop staging and hospital camp in Étaples in France has been theorized by virologist John Oxford as being at the center of the Spanish flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] His study found that in late 1916 the Étaples camp was hit by a new disease with high mortality that caused symptoms similar to the flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] According to Oxford, a similar outbreak occurred in March 1917 at army barracks in Aldershot, and military pathologists later recognized these early outbreaks as the same disease as the Spanish flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The overcrowded camp and hospital at Étaples was an ideal environment for the spread of a respiratory virus.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The hospital treated thousands of victims of poison gas attacks, and other casualties of war.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It also was home to a piggery, and poultry was regularly brought in to feed the camp.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Oxford and his team postulated that a precursor virus, harbored in birds, mutated and then migrated to pigs kept near the front.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A report published in 2016 in the *Journal of the Chinese Medical Association* found evidence that the 1918 virus had been circulating in the European armies for months and possibly years before the 1918 pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Political scientist Andrew Price-Smith published data from the Austrian archives suggesting the influenza began in Austria in early 1917.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Hannoun considered several alternative hypotheses of origin, such as Spain, Kansas, and Brest, as being possible, but not likely.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In 2014, historian Mark Humphries of the Memorial University of Newfoundland argued that the mobilization of 96,000 Chinese laborers to work behind the British and French lines might have been the source of the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Humphries found archival evidence that a respiratory illness that struck northern China (where the laborers came from) in November 1917 was identified a year later by Chinese health officials as identical to the Spanish flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] No tissue samples have survived for modern comparison.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Nevertheless, there were some reports of respiratory illness on the path the laborers took to get to Europe, which also passed through North America.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] China was one of the few regions of the world seemingly less affected by the Spanish flu pandemic, where several studies have documented a comparatively mild flu season in 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] (This is disputed due to lack of data during the Warlord Period.) This has led to speculation that the Spanish flu pandemic originated in China, as the lower mortality rates may be explained by the Chinese population's previously acquired immunity to the flu virus.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the Guangdong Province it was reported that early outbreaks of influenza in 1918 disproportionately impacted young men.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The June outbreak infected children and adolescents between 11 and 20 years of age, while the October outbreak was most common in those aged 11 to 15.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A report published in 2016 in the *Journal of the Chinese Medical Association* found no evidence that the 1918 virus was imported to Europe via Chinese and Southeast Asian soldiers and workers and instead found evidence of its circulation in Europe before the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Further evidence against the disease being spread by Chinese workers was that workers entered Europe through other routes that did not result in a detectable spread, making them unlikely to have been the original hosts.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The pandemic is conventionally marked as having begun on 4 March 1918 with the recording of the case of Albert Gitchell, an army cook at Camp Funston in Kansas despite there having been cases before him.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The disease had already been observed 200 miles (320 km) away in Haskell County as early as January 1918, prompting local doctor Loring Miner to warn the editors of the U.S.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Public Health Service's journal *Public Health Reports*.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Within days of the 4 March case at Camp Funston, 522 men at the camp had reported sick.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By 11 March 1918, the virus had reached Queens, New York.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Failure to take preventive measures in March/April was later criticized.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] As the U.S. had entered World War I, the disease quickly spread from Camp Funston, a major training ground for troops of the American Expeditionary Forces, to other U.S.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Army camps and Europe, becoming an epidemic in the Midwest, East Coast, and French ports by April 1918, and reaching the Western Front by mid-April.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It then quickly spread to the rest of France, Great Britain, Italy, and Spain and in May reached Wrocław and Odessa.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After the signing of the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk (March 1918), Germany started releasing Russian prisoners of war, who brought the disease to their country.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It reached North Africa, India, and Japan in May, and soon after had likely gone around the world as there had been recorded cases in Southeast Asia in April.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In June an outbreak was reported in China.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After reaching Australia in July, the wave started to recede.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The first wave lasted from the first quarter of 1918 and was relatively mild.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mortality rates were not appreciably above normal; in the United States ~75,000 flu-related deaths were reported in the first six months of 1918, compared to ~63,000 deaths during the same time period in 1915.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Madrid, Spain, fewer than 1,000 people died from influenza between May and June 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There were no reported quarantines; the first wave caused a significant disruption in the military operations of World War I, with three-quarters of French troops, half the British forces, and over 900,000 German soldiers sick.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second wave began in the second half of August 1918, probably spreading to Boston, Massachusetts and Freetown, Sierra Leone, by ships from Brest, where it had likely arrived with American troops or French recruits for naval training.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] From the Boston Navy Yard and Camp Devens, about 30 miles (48 km) west of Boston, other U.S. military sites were soon afflicted, as were troops being transported to Europe.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Helped by troop movements, it spread over the next two months to all of North America, and then to Central and South America, also reaching Brazil and the Caribbean on ships.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In July 1918, the Ottoman Empire saw its first cases, in soldiers.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] From Freetown, the pandemic spread through West Africa along the coast, rivers, and railways, and from railheads to more remote communities, while South Africa received it in September on ships bringing back members of the South African Native Labour Corps from France.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] From there it spread around southern Africa and beyond the Zambezi, reaching Ethiopia in November.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] On 15 September, New York City saw its first fatality from influenza.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The Philadelphia Liberty Loans Parade, held in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on 28 September 1918 to promote government bonds for World War I, resulted in an outbreak causing 12,000 deaths.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The celebrations of the Armistice of 11 November 1918 also caused outbreaks in Lima and Nairobi, but by December the wave was mostly over.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second wave of the 1918 pandemic was much more deadly than the first.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The first wave had resembled typical flu epidemics; those most at risk were the sick and elderly, while younger, healthier people recovered easily.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] October 1918 was the month with the highest fatality rate of the whole pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the United States, ~292,000 deaths were reported between September–December 1918, compared to ~26,000 during the same time period in 1915.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The Netherlands reported over 40,000 deaths from influenza and acute respiratory disease.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Bombay reported ~15,000 deaths in a population of 1.1 million.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The 1918 flu pandemic in India was especially deadly, as Historian David Arnold estimates at least 12 million dead, about 5% of the population.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Pandemic activity persisted into 1919 in many places, possibly attributable to climate, specifically in the Northern Hemisphere, where it was winter and thus the usual time for influenza activity.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The pandemic nonetheless continued into 1919 largely independent of region and climate.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Cases began to rise again in some parts of the U.S. as early as late November 1918, with the Public Health Service issuing its first report of a "recrudescence of the disease" in "widely scattered localities" in early December.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This resurgent activity varied across the country, however, possibly on account of differing restrictions.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Michigan, for example, experienced a swift resurgence of influenza that reached its peak in December, possibly as a result of the lifting of the ban on public gatherings.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Pandemic interventions, such as bans on public gatherings and the closing of schools, were reimposed in many places in an attempt to suppress the spread.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There was "a very sudden and very marked rise in general death rate" in most cities in January 1919; nearly all experienced "some degree of recrudescence" of the flu in January and February.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Significant outbreaks occurred in cities including Los Angeles, New York City, Memphis, Nashville, San Francisco, and St.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By 21 February, with some local variation, influenza activity was reported to have been declining since mid-January in all parts of the country.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Following this "first great epidemic period" that had commenced in October 1918, deaths from pneumonia and influenza were "somewhat below average" in large U.S. cities between May 1919 and January 1920.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Nonetheless, nearly 160,000 deaths were attributed to these causes in the first six months of 1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It was not until later in the winter and into the spring that a clearer resurgence appeared in Europe.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A significant third wave had developed in England and Wales by mid-February, peaking in early March, though it did not fully subside until May.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] France also experienced a significant wave that peaked in February, alongside the Netherlands.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Norway, Finland, and Switzerland saw recrudescences of pandemic activity in March, and Sweden in April.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Much of Spain was affected by "a substantial recrudescent wave" of influenza between January and April 1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Portugal experienced a resurgence in pandemic activity that lasted from March to September 1919, with the greatest impact being felt on the west coast and in the north of the country; all districts were affected between April and May specifically.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Influenza entered Australia for the first time in January 1919 after a strict maritime quarantine had shielded the country through 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It assumed epidemic proportions first in Melbourne, peaking in mid-February.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The flu soon appeared in neighboring New South Wales and South Australia.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] New South Wales experienced its first wave of infection between mid-March and late May, while a second, more severe wave occurred in Victoria between April and June.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Land quarantine measures hindered the spread of the disease.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Queensland was not infected until late April; Western Australia avoided the disease until early June, and Tasmania remained free from it until mid-August.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Out of the six states, Victoria and New South Wales experienced generally more extensive epidemics.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Each experienced another significant wave of illness over the winter.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second epidemic in New South Wales was more severe than the first, while Victoria saw a third wave that was somewhat less extensive than its second, more akin to its first.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The disease also reached other parts of the world for the first time in 1919, such as Madagascar, which saw its first cases in April; the outbreak had spread to practically all sections of the island by June.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In other parts, influenza recurred in the form of a true "third wave".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Hong Kong experienced another outbreak in June, as did South Africa during its fall and winter months in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] New Zealand experienced some cases in May.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Parts of South America experienced a resurgence of pandemic activity throughout 1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A third wave hit Brazil between January and June.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Between July 1919 and February 1920, Chile, which had been affected for the first time in October 1918, experienced a severe second wave, with mortality peaking in August 1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Montevideo similarly experienced a second outbreak between July and September.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The third wave particularly affected Spain, Serbia, Mexico and Great Britain, resulting in hundreds of thousands of deaths.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the Northern Hemisphere, fears of a "recurrence" of the flu grew as fall approached.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Experts cited past flu epidemics, such as that of 1889–1890, to predict that such a recurrence a year later was not unlikely, though not all agreed.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Surgeon General Rupert Blue said a return of the flu later in the year would "probably, but by no means certainly," occur.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] France had readied a public information campaign before the end of the summer, and Britain began preparations in the autumn with the manufacture of vaccine.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Japan, the flu broke out again in December and spread rapidly throughout the country, a fact attributed at the time to cold weather.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Pandemic-related measures were renewed to check the outbreak, and health authorities recommended the use of masks.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The epidemic intensified in the latter part of December before swiftly peaking in January.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Between October 1919 and 23 January 1920, 780,000 cases were reported across the country, with at least 20,000 deaths recorded by that date.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This apparently reflected "a condition of severity three times greater than for the corresponding period of" 1918–1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Nonetheless, the disease was regarded as being milder than it had been the year before, albeit more infectious.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Despite its rapid peak at the beginning of the year, the outbreak persisted throughout the winter, before subsiding in the spring.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the United States, there were "almost continuously isolated or solitary cases" of flu throughout the spring and summer of 1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] An increase in scattered cases became apparent as early as September, but Chicago experienced one of the first major outbreaks of the flu beginning in the middle of January.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The Public Health Service announced it would take steps to "localize the epidemic", but the disease was already causing a simultaneous outbreak in Kansas City and quickly spread outward from the center of the country.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A few days after its first announcement, PHS issued another assuring that the disease was under the control of state health authorities and that an outbreak of epidemic proportions was not expected.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It became apparent within days of the start of Chicago's explosive growth in cases that the flu was spreading in the city at an even faster rate than in winter 1919, though fewer were dying.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Within a week, new cases in the city had surpassed its peak during the 1919 wave.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Around the same time, New York City began to see its own sudden increase in cases, and other cities around the country were soon to follow.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Certain pandemic restrictions, such as the closing of schools and theaters and the staggering of business hours to avoid congestion, were reimposed in cities like Chicago, Memphis, and New York City.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] As they had during the epidemic in fall 1918, schools in New York City remained open, while those in Memphis were shuttered as part of restrictions on public gatherings.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The fourth wave in the United States subsided as swiftly as it had appeared, reaching a peak in early February.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] "An epidemic of considerable proportions marked the early months of 1920", the U.S.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mortality Statistics would later note; according to data at this time, the epidemic resulted in one third as many deaths as the 1918–1919 experience.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] New York City alone reported 6,374 deaths between December 1919 and April 1920, almost twice the number of the first wave in spring 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Detroit, Milwaukee, Kansas City, Minneapolis, and St.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Louis were hit particularly hard, with death rates higher than all of 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Hawaii experienced its peak of the pandemic in early 1920, recording 1,489 deaths from flu-related causes, compared with 615 in 1918 and 796 in 1919.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By contrast, the outbreak in western Europe was considered "benign", with the age distribution of deaths beginning to take on that of seasonal flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Spain, Denmark, Finland, Germany and Switzerland recorded a late peak between January–April 1920.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mexico experienced a fourth wave between February and March.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In South America, Peru experienced "asynchronous recrudescent waves" throughout the year.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A severe third wave hit Lima, the capital city, between January and March, resulting in an all-cause excess mortality rate approximately four times greater than that of the 1918–1919 wave.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Ica similarly experienced another severe pandemic wave in 1920, between July and October.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A fourth wave also occurred in Brazil, in February.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Korea and Taiwan experienced pronounced outbreaks in late 1919 and early 1920.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By mid-1920, the pandemic was largely considered to be "over" by the public as well as governments.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Though parts of Chile experienced a third, milder wave between November 1920 and March 1921, the flu seemed to be mostly absent through the winter of 1920–1921.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the United States, for example, deaths from pneumonia and influenza were "very much lower than for many years".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Seasonal influenza began to be reported again from many places in 1921.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Influenza continued to be felt in Chile, where a post-pandemic fourth wave affected 7 of its 24 provinces between June and December 1921.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The winter of 1921–1922 was the first major reappearance of seasonal influenza in the Northern Hemisphere, in many parts its most significant occurrence since the main pandemic in late 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Northwestern Europe was particularly affected.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] All-cause mortality in the Netherlands approximately doubled in January 1922 alone.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Helsinki, a major epidemic (the fifth since 1918) prevailed between November and December 1921.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The flu was also widespread in the United States, its prevalence in California reportedly greater in early March 1922 than at any point since the pandemic ended in 1920.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the years after 1920, the disease came to represent the "seasonal flu".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The virus, H1N1, remained endemic, occasionally causing more severe or otherwise notable outbreaks.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The period since its initial appearance in 1918 has been termed a "pandemic era", in which all flu pandemics have been caused by its own descendants.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Following the first of these post-1918 pandemics, in 1957, the virus was totally displaced by the novel H2N2, the reassortant product of the human H1N1 and an avian influenza virus, which thereafter became the active influenza A virus in humans.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In 1977, an influenza virus bearing a very close resemblance to the seasonal H1N1, which had not been seen since the 1950s, appeared in the USSR and subsequently initiated a "technical" pandemic that principally affected those 26 and under.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Following this miniature pandemic, the reemerged H1N1 became endemic again but did not displace the other active influenza A virus, H3N2 (which itself had displaced H2N2 through a pandemic in 1968).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] For the first time, two influenza A viruses were observed in cocirculation.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This state has persisted even after 2009, when a novel H1N1 virus emerged, sparked a pandemic, and thereafter took the place of the seasonal H1N1 to circulate alongside H3N2.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The basic reproduction number of the virus was between 2 and 3.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The close quarters and massive troop movements of World War I hastened the pandemic, and probably both increased transmission and augmented mutation.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The war may also have reduced people's resistance to the virus.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Some speculate the soldiers' immune systems were weakened by malnourishment and the stresses of combat and chemical attacks, increasing their susceptibility.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Modern transportation systems and increased travel was a significant factor in the worldwide occurrence.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Another was lies and denial by governments, leaving the population ill-prepared to handle the outbreaks.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The severity of the second wave has been attributed to the First World War.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In civilian life, natural selection favors a mild strain.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Those who get very ill stay home, and those mildly ill continue with their lives, preferentially spreading the mild strain.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the trenches, natural selection was reversed.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Soldiers with a mild strain stayed where they were, while the severely ill were sent on crowded trains to crowded field hospitals, spreading the deadlier virus.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second wave began, and the flu quickly spread around the world again.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] (During modern pandemics, health officials look for deadlier strains of a virus when it reaches places with social upheaval.) The fact that most of those who recovered from first-wave infections had become immune showed that it must have been the same strain of flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This was most dramatically illustrated in Copenhagen, which escaped with a combined mortality rate of 0.29% (0.02% in the first wave and 0.27% in the second wave) because of exposure to the less-lethal first wave.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After the lethal second wave, new cases dropped abruptly.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Philadelphia, for example, 4,597 people died in the week ending 16 October, but by 11 November, influenza had almost disappeared from the city.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] One explanation for the rapid decline in lethality is that doctors became more effective in the prevention and treatment of pneumonia that developed after the victims had contracted the virus.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, John Barry stated in his 2004 book *The Great Influenza: The Epic Story of the Deadliest Plague In History* that researchers have found no evidence to support this position.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Another theory holds that the 1918 virus mutated extremely rapidly to a less lethal strain.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Such evolution of influenza is a common occurrence: there is a tendency for pathogenic viruses to become less lethal with time, as the hosts of more dangerous strains tend to die out.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Fatal cases did continue into 1919, however.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] One notable example was that of ice hockey player Joe Hall, who died of the flu in April after an outbreak that resulted in the cancellation of the 1919 Stanley Cup Final.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The majority of the infected experienced only the typical flu symptoms of sore throat, headache, and fever, especially during the first wave.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, during the second wave, the disease was much more serious, often complicated by bacterial pneumonia, which was often the cause of death.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This more serious type would cause *heliotrope cyanosis* to develop, whereby the skin would first develop two mahogany spots over the cheekbones which would then over a few hours color the entire face blue, followed by black coloration first in the extremities and then the limbs and the torso.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Death would follow within hours or days due to the lungs being filled with fluids.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Other signs and symptoms reported included spontaneous mouth and nosebleeds, miscarriages for pregnant women, a peculiar smell, teeth and hair falling out, delirium, dizziness, insomnia, loss of hearing or smell, and impaired vision.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] One observer wrote, "One of the most striking of the complications was hemorrhage from mucous membranes, especially from the nose, stomach, and intestine.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Bleeding from the ears and petechial hemorrhages in the skin also occurred".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The majority of deaths were from bacterial pneumonia, a common secondary infection associated with influenza.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This pneumonia was itself caused by common upper respiratory-tract bacteria, which were able to get into the lungs via the damaged bronchial tubes.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The virus also killed people directly by causing massive hemorrhages and edema in the lungs.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Modern analysis has shown the virus to be particularly deadly because in animal trials it triggers an overreaction of the body's immune system (cytokine storm).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The strong immune reactions of young adults were postulated to have ravaged the body, whereas the weaker immune reactions of children and middle-aged adults resulted in fewer deaths.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Because the virus that caused the disease was too small to be seen under a microscope at the time, there were problems with correctly diagnosing it.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The bacterium *Haemophilus influenzae* was instead mistakenly thought to be the cause, as it was big enough to be seen and was present in many, though not all, patients.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] For this reason, a vaccine that was used against that bacillus did not make infection rarer but did decrease the death rate.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] During the deadly second wave there were also fears that it was in fact plague, dengue fever, or cholera.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Another misdiagnosis was typhus, which was common in circumstances of social upheaval, and was therefore also affecting Russia in the aftermath of the October Revolution.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Chile, the view of the country's elite was that the nation was in severe decline, and therefore doctors assumed that the disease was typhus caused by poor hygiene, causing a mismanaged response which did not ban mass gatherings.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Studies have shown that the immune system of Spanish flu victims could have been weakened by unseasonably cold and wet weather for extended periods during the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This affected especially troops exposed to incessant rains and lower-than-average temperatures during World War I, and especially during the second wave of the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Specifically, a significant increase in precipitation affected all of Europe during the second wave of the pandemic, from September to December 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mortality figures follow closely the concurrent increase in precipitation and decrease in temperatures.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The climate anomaly likely influenced the migration of H1N1 avian vectors which contaminate bodies of water with their droppings, reaching 60% infection rates in autumn.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The climate anomaly has been associated with an anthropogenic increase in atmospheric dust, due to the incessant bombardment; increased nucleation due to dust particles (cloud condensation nuclei) contributed to increased precipitation.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In September 1918, the Red Cross recommended two-layer gauze masks to halt the spread of "plague".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] , limitations on crowd size, selective closing of businesses, curfews, and lockdowns.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After October's strict containment measures showed some success, Armistice Day celebrations in November and relaxed attitudes by Thanksgiving caused a resurgence.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] While systems for alerting public health authorities of infectious spread did exist in 1918, they did not generally include influenza, leading to a delayed response.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Maritime quarantines were declared on islands such as Iceland, Australia, and American Samoa, saving many lives.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Social distancing measures were introduced, for example closing schools, theatres, and places of worship, limiting public transportation, and banning mass gatherings.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Wearing face masks became common in some places, such as Japan, though there were debates over their efficacy.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There was also some resistance to their use, as exemplified by the Anti-Mask League of San Francisco.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Vaccines were developed, but as these were based on bacteria and not the actual virus, they could only help with secondary infections.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] To a large extent, the New York City health commissioner ordered businesses to open and close on staggered shifts to avoid overcrowding on the subways.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A later study found that measures such as banning mass gatherings and requiring the wearing of face masks could cut the death rate up to 50 percent, but this was dependent on their being imposed early in the outbreak and not being lifted prematurely.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] As there were no antiviral drugs to treat the virus, and no antibiotics to treat the secondary bacterial infections, doctors would rely on an assortment of medicines with varying degrees of effectiveness, such as aspirin, quinine, arsenics, digitalis, strychnine, epsom salts, castor oil, and iodine.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Traditional treatments, such as bloodletting, ayurveda, and kampo, were also applied.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Due to World War I, many countries engaged in wartime censorship, and suppressed reporting of the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] For example, the Italian newspaper *Corriere della Sera* was prohibited from reporting daily death tolls.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The newspapers of the time were also generally paternalistic and worried about mass panic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Misinformation also spread along with the disease.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Ireland there was a belief that noxious gases were rising from the mass graves of Flanders Fields and being "blown all over the world by winds".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There were also rumors that the Germans were behind it, for example by poisoning the aspirin manufactured by Bayer, or by releasing poison gas from U-boats.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The Spanish flu infected around 500 million people, about one-third of the world's population.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Estimates on deaths vary greatly, but it is considered to be one of the deadliest pandemics in history.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] An early estimate from 1927 put global mortality at 21.6 million.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] An estimate from 1991 states that the virus killed between 25 and 39 million people.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2005 estimate put the death toll at 50 million, and possibly as high as 100 million.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, a 2018 reassessment in the *American Journal of Epidemiology* estimated the total to be about 17 million, though this has been contested.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Barry have the total death toll alone at well above 100 million.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] With a world population of 1.8 to 1.9 billion, these estimates correspond to between 1 and 6 percent of the population.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2009 study in *Influenza and Other Respiratory Viruses* based on data from fourteen European countries estimated a total of 2.64 million excess deaths in Europe attributable to the Spanish flu during the 1918–1919 phase of the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This represents a mortality rate of about 1.1% of the European population (c.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] 250 million in 1918), considerably higher than the mortality rate in the U.S., which the authors hypothesize is likely due to the severe effects of the war in Europe.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The excess mortality rate in the U.K. has been estimated at 0.28%–0.4%, far below this European average.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some 12–17 million people died in India, about 5% of the population.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The death toll in India's British-ruled districts was 13.88 million.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another estimate gives at least 12 million dead.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The decade between 1911 and 1921 was the only census period in which India's population fell, mostly due to devastation of the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Japan, the flu killed nearly 500,000 people over two waves between 1918 and 1920, with nearly 300,000 excess deaths between October 1918 and May 1919 and 182,000 between December 1919 and May 1920.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the Dutch East Indies (now Indonesia), 1.5 million were assumed to have died among 30 million inhabitants.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Tahiti, 13% of the population died in one month.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarly, in Western Samoa 22% of the population of 38,000 died within two months.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Istanbul, capital of the Ottoman Empire, 6,403 to 10,000 died, giving the city a mortality rate of at least 0.56%.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In New Zealand, the flu killed an estimated 6,400 *Pākehā* (or "New Zealanders primarily of European descent") and 2,500 Māori in six weeks, with Māori dying at eight times the rate of *Pākehā*.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Australia, the flu killed around 12,000 to 20,000 people.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The country's death rate, 2.7 per 1,000 people, was one of the lowest recorded; however, as much as 40 percent of the population were infected, and a mortality rate of 50 percent was recorded by some Aboriginal communities.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] New South Wales and Victoria saw the greatest relative mortality, with 3.19 and 2.40 deaths per 1,000 people respectively, while Western Australia, Queensland, Southern Australia, and Tasmania experienced rates of 1.70, 1.14, 1.13, and 1.09 per 1,000 respectively.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Queensland, at least one-third of deaths recorded were in the Aboriginal population.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the U.S., about 20 million out of a population of 105 million became infected in the 1918–1919 season, and an estimated 500,000 to 850,000 died (0.5 to 0.8 percent of the U.S. population).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Native Americans tribes were particularly affected.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the Four Corners area, there were 3,293 registered deaths among Native Americans.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Entire Inuit and Alaskan Native village communities died in Alaska.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Brazil, 300,000 died, including president Rodrigues Alves.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the UK, as many as 250,000 died; in France, more than 400,000.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Ghana, the influenza epidemic killed at least 100,000 people.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Tafari Makonnen (the future Emperor of Ethiopia) was one of the first Ethiopians who contracted influenza but survived.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Estimates for fatalities in the capital city, Addis Ababa, range from 5,000 to 10,000, or higher.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The death toll in Russia has been estimated at 450,000, though the epidemiologists who suggested this number called it a "shot in the dark".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] If it is correct, Russia lost roughly 0.4% of its population, meaning it suffered the lowest influenza-related mortality in Europe.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another study considers this number unlikely, given that the country was in the grip of a civil war, and the infrastructure of daily life had broken down; the study suggests that Russia's death toll was closer to 2%, or 2.7 million people.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Even in areas where mortality was low, so many adults were incapacitated that daily life was hampered.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some communities closed all stores or required customers to leave orders outside.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There were reports that healthcare workers could not tend the sick nor the gravediggers bury the dead because they too were ill.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Mass graves were dug by steam shovel and bodies buried without coffins in many places.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Bristol Bay, a region of Alaska populated by Indigenous people, suffered a death rate of 40 percent, with some villages entirely disappearing.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Nenana, Alaska, avoided the extent of the pandemic between 1918 and 1919, but the flu at last reached the town in spring 1920.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Reports suggested that during the first two weeks of May, the majority of the town's population became infected; 10% of the population were estimated to have died, most of whom were Alaska Natives.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Several Pacific island territories were hit particularly hard.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The pandemic reached them from New Zealand, which was too slow to implement measures to prevent ships carrying the flu from leaving its ports.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] From New Zealand, the flu reached Tonga (killing 8% of the population), Nauru (16%), and Fiji (5%, 9,000 people).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Worst affected was Western Samoa, which had been occupied by New Zealand in 1914.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] 90% of the population was infected; 30% of adult men, 22% of adult women, and 10% of children died.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The disease spread fastest through the higher social classes among the Indigenous peoples, because of the custom of gathering oral tradition from chiefs on their deathbeds; many community elders were infected through this process.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Iran, the mortality was estimated at between 902,400 and 2,431,000, or 8% to 22% of the total population.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The country was going through the Persian famine of 1917–1919 concurrently.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Ireland, during the worst 12 months, the Spanish flu accounted for one-third of all deaths.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In South Africa it is estimated that about 300,000 people amounting to 6% of the population died within six weeks.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Government actions in the early stages of the virus' arrival in the country in September 1918 are believed to have unintentionally accelerated its spread.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Almost a quarter of the working population of Kimberley, consisting of workers in the diamond mines, died.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In British Somaliland, one official estimated that 7% of the native population died.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This huge death toll resulted from an extremely high infection rate of up to 50% and the extreme severity of the symptoms.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the Pacific, American Samoa and the French colony of New Caledonia succeeded in preventing even a single death from influenza through effective quarantines.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, the outbreak was delayed into 1926 for American Samoa and 1921 for New Caledonia as the quarantine period ended.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] On American Samoa, at least 25% of the island residents were clinically attacked and 0.1% died, and on New Caledonia, there was widespread illness and 0.1% population died.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Australia also managed to avoid the first two waves with a quarantine.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Iceland protected a third of its population from exposure by blocking the main road of the island.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] By the end of the pandemic, the isolated island of Marajó, in Brazil's Amazon River Delta had not reported an outbreak.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Estimates for the death toll in China have varied widely, reflecting the lack of centralized collection of health data at the time due to the Warlord period.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] China may have experienced a relatively mild flu season in 1918 compared to other areas of the world.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, some reports from its interior suggest that mortality rates from influenza were perhaps higher in at least a few locations in 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] At the very least, there is little evidence that China as a whole was seriously affected by the flu compared to other countries.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The first estimate of the Chinese death toll was made in 1991 by Patterson and Pyle, which estimated a toll of between 5 and 9 million.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, this study was criticized by later studies due to flawed methodology, and newer studies have published estimates of a far lower mortality rate in China.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] For instance, Iijima in 1998 estimates the death toll in China to be between 1 and 1.28 million based on data available from Chinese port cities.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The lower estimates of the Chinese death toll are based on the low mortality rates that were found in Chinese port cities and on the assumption that poor communications prevented the flu from penetrating the interior of China.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, some contemporary newspaper and post office reports, as well as reports from missionary doctors, suggest that the flu did penetrate the Chinese interior and that influenza was severe in at least some locations in the countryside of China.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Although medical records from China's interior are lacking, extensive medical data were recorded in Chinese port cities, such as then British-controlled Hong Kong, Canton, Peking, Harbin and Shanghai.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These data were collected by the Chinese Maritime Customs Service, which was largely staffed by non-Chinese foreigners.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] As a whole, data from China's port cities show low mortality rates compared to other cities in Asia.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] For example, the British authorities at Hong Kong and Canton reported a mortality rate from influenza at a rate of 0.25% and 0.32%, much lower than the reported mortality rate of other cities in Asia, such as Calcutta or Bombay, where influenza was much more devastating.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarly, in the city of Shanghai – which had a population of over 2 million – there were only 266 recorded deaths from influenza among the Chinese population in 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] If extrapolated from the extensive data recorded from Chinese cities, the suggested mortality rate from influenza in China as a whole in 1918 was likely lower than 1% – much lower than the world average (which was around 3–5%).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In contrast, Japan and Taiwan had reported a mortality rate from influenza around 0.45% and 0.69% respectively, higher than the mortality rate collected from data in Chinese port cities, such as Hong Kong (0.25%), Canton (0.32%), and Shanghai.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, the influenza mortality rate in Hong Kong and Canton are under-recorded, because only the deaths that occurred in colony hospitals were counted.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarly, in Shanghai, these statistics are limited to that area of the city under the control of the health section of the Shanghai International Settlement; the actual death toll in Shanghai was much higher.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The medical records from China's interior indicate that, compared to cities, rural communities have substantially higher mortality rate.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A published influenza survey in Houlu County, Hebei Province, found that the case fatality rate was 9.77% and 0.79% of county population died from influenza in October and November 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The pandemic mostly killed young adults.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 1918–1919, 99% of pandemic influenza deaths in the U.S. occurred in people under 65, and nearly half of deaths were in young adults 20 to 40 years old.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 1920, the mortality rate among people under 65 had decreased sixfold to half the mortality rate of people over 65, but 92% of deaths still occurred in people under 65.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This is unusual since influenza is typically most deadly to weak individuals, such as infants under age two, adults over age 70, and the immunocompromised.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 1918, older adults may have had partial protection caused by exposure to the 1889–1890 flu pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Barry, the most vulnerable of all were pregnant women.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] He reported that in thirteen studies of hospitalized women in the pandemic, the death rate ranged from 23% to 71%.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Of the pregnant women who survived childbirth, over one-quarter (26%) lost the child.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another oddity was that the outbreak was widespread in the summer and autumn (in the Northern Hemisphere); influenza is usually worse in winter.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There were also geographic patterns to the disease's fatality.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some parts of Asia had 30 times higher death rates than some parts of Europe, and generally, Africa and Asia had higher rates, while Europe and North America had lower ones.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There was also great variation within continents, with three times higher mortality in Hungary and Spain compared to Denmark, two to three times higher chance of death in Sub-Saharan Africa compared to North Africa, and possibly up to ten times higher rates between the extremes of Asia.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Cities were affected worse than rural areas.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There were also differences between cities, which might have reflected exposure to the milder first wave giving immunity, as well as the introduction of social distancing measures.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another major pattern was the differences between social classes.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Oslo, death rates were inversely correlated with apartment size, as the poorer people living in smaller apartments died at a higher rate.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Social status was also reflected in the higher mortality among immigrant communities, with Italian Americans, a recently arrived group at the time, nearly twice as likely to die compared to the average Americans.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These disparities reflected worse diets, crowded living conditions, and problems accessing healthcare.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Paradoxically, however, African Americans were relatively spared.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] More men than women were killed by the flu, as they were more likely to go out and be exposed, while women tended to stay at home.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] For the same reason men also were more likely to have pre-existing tuberculosis, which severely worsened the chances of recovery.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, in India the opposite was true, potentially because Indian women were neglected with poorer nutrition, and were expected to care for the sick.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] (2011) examined the factors that underlie variability in temporal patterns and their correlation to patterns of mortality and morbidity.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Their analysis suggests that temporal variations in transmission rate provide the best explanation, and the variation in transmission required to generate these three waves is within biologically plausible values.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] (2013) used a simple epidemic model incorporating three factors to infer the cause of the three waves of the 1918 influenza pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These factors were school opening and closing, temperature changes throughout the outbreak, and human behavioral changes in response to the outbreak.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Their modeling results showed that all three factors are important, but human behavioral responses showed the most significant effects.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Academic Andrew Price-Smith has argued that the virus helped tip the balance of power in the latter days of the war towards the Allied cause.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] He provides data that the viral waves hit the Central Powers before the Allied powers and that morbidity and mortality in Germany and Austria were considerably higher than in Britain and France.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2006 *Lancet* study corroborates higher excess mortality rates in Germany (0.76%) and Austria (1.61%) compared to Britain (0.34%) and France (0.75%).
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Kenneth Kahn at Oxford University Computing Services writes that "Many researchers have suggested that the conditions of the war significantly aided the spread of the disease.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] And others have argued that the course of the war (and subsequent peace treaty) was influenced by the pandemic." Kahn has developed a model that can be used to test these theories.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Many businesses in the entertainment and service industries suffered losses in revenue, while the healthcare industry reported profit gains.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Historian Nancy Bristow has argued that the pandemic, when combined with the increasing number of women attending college, contributed to the success of women in nursing.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This was due in part to the failure of medical doctors, who were predominantly men, to contain the illness.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Nursing staff, who were mainly women, celebrated the success of their patient care and did not associate the spread of the disease with their work.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2020 study found that U.S. cities that implemented early and extensive non-medical measures (quarantine, etc.) suffered no additional adverse economic effects due to implementing those measures.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, the validity of this study has been questioned because of the coincidence of WWI and other problems with data reliability.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The flu has also been linked to the outbreak of encephalitis lethargica in the 1920s.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Survivors faced an elevated mortality risk.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some survivors did not fully recover from physiological conditions resulting from infection.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The Spanish flu began to fade from public awareness over the decades until the bird flu and other pandemics in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This has led some historians to label the Spanish flu a "forgotten pandemic".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, this label has been challenged by the historian Guy Beiner, who demonstrated how the pandemic was overshadowed by the commemoration of the First World War and mostly neglected in mainstream historiography, yet was remembered in private and local traditions across the globe.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There are various theories of why the Spanish flu was "forgotten".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The rapid pace of the pandemic, which killed most of its victims in the United States within less than nine months, resulted in limited media coverage.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The general population was familiar with patterns of pandemic disease in the late 19th and early 20th centuries: typhoid, yellow fever, diphtheria, and cholera all occurred near the same time.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These outbreaks probably lessened the significance of the influenza pandemic for the public.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In some areas, the flu was not reported on, the only mention being that of advertisements for medicines claiming to cure it.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Additionally, the outbreak coincided with the deaths and media focus on the First World War.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The majority of fatalities, from both the war and the epidemic, were among young adults.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The high number of war-related deaths of young adults may have overshadowed the deaths caused by flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Particularly in Europe, where the war's toll was high, the flu may not have had a tremendous psychological impact or may have seemed an extension of the war's tragedies.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The last known person to have survived the Spanish flu, José Ameal Peña, was alive as of 2020.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Despite the toll of the pandemic, it was never a large theme in American literature.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Alfred Crosby suspects it was overshadowed by World War I.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Katherine Anne Porter's 1939 novella *Pale Horse, Pale Rider* is one of the most well-known fictional accounts of the pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The 2006 novel *The Last Town on Earth* focuses on a town which attempts to limit the spread of the flu by preventing people from entering or leaving.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] *The Pull of the Stars* is a 2020 novel by Emma Donoghue set in Dublin during the Spanish flu.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Publishers fast-tracked publication because of the then ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarities between a reconstruction of the virus and avian viruses, combined with the human pandemic preceding the first reports of influenza in swine, led researchers to conclude the influenza virus jumped directly from birds to humans, and swine caught the disease from humans.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] More recent research has suggested the strain may have originated in a nonhuman, mammalian species, in 1882–1913.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This ancestor virus diverged about 1913–1915 into the classical swine and human H1N1 influenza lineages.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The last common ancestor of human strains dates between February 1917 and April 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Because pigs are more readily infected with avian influenza viruses than are humans, they were suggested as the original recipients of the virus, passing the virus to humans sometime between 1913 and 1918.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] An effort to recreate the Spanish flu strain (a strain of influenza A subtype H1N1) was a collaboration among the Armed Forces Institute of Pathology, the USDA ARS Southeast Poultry Research Laboratory, and Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York City.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The effort resulted in the announcement in 2005 that the group had successfully determined the virus' genetic sequence, using historic tissue samples recovered by pathologist Johan Hultin from an Inuit female flu victim buried in the Alaskan permafrost and samples preserved from American soldiers.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This enabled researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the Mount Sinai School of Medicine, led by Dr Terrence Tumpey, to synthesize RNA segments from the H1N1 virus and reconstruct infective virus particles.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These were subsequently used to experimentally infect mice, ferrets, and macaques, providing information about how to prevent and control future pandemics.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 2007, Kobasa et al. reported that monkeys (*Macaca fascicularis*) infected with the recreated flu strain exhibited classic symptoms of the 1918 pandemic, and died from an overreaction of the immune system.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This may explain why the Spanish flu had its surprising effect on younger, healthier people, as a person with a stronger immune system would potentially have a stronger overreaction.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In December 2008, research by Yoshihiro Kawaoka of the University of Wisconsin linked three specific genes (termed PA, PB1, and PB2) and a nucleoprotein derived from Spanish flu samples to the ability of the 1918 flu virus to invade the lungs and cause pneumonia.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These genes were inserted into a modern H1N1 strain and triggered similar symptoms in animal testing.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In June 2010, a team at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine reported the 2009 flu pandemic vaccine provided some cross-protection against the Spanish flu pandemic strain.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 2013, the AIR Worldwide Research and Modeling Group "estimated the effects of a similar pandemic occurring today using the AIR Pandemic Flu Model".
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the model, "a modern-day 'Spanish flu' event would result in additional life insurance losses of between US$15.3–27.8 billion in the United States alone", with 188,000–337,000 deaths in the United States.
[src:tonga/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Worobey extracted tissue from the slides to potentially reveal more about the origin of the pathogen.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The **1987 Rugby World Cup** was the first Rugby World Cup.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] It was co-hosted by New Zealand and Australia – New Zealand hosted 21 matches (17 pool stage matches, two quarter-finals, the third-place play-off and the final) while Australia hosted 11 matches (seven pool matches, two quarter-finals and both semi-finals).
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The tournament was won by New Zealand, who were the strong favourites and won all their matches comfortably.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] New Zealand defeated France 29–9 in the final at Eden Park in Auckland.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The New Zealand team was captained by David Kirk and included such rugby greats as Sean Fitzpatrick, John Kirwan, Grant Fox and Michael Jones.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] Wales finished third, and Australia fourth, after conceding crucial tries in the dying seconds of both their semi-final against France and the third-place play-off against Wales.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] Seven of the sixteen participating teams were the International Rugby Football Board (IRFB) members – New Zealand, Australia, England, Scotland, Ireland, Wales and France.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] South Africa was unable to compete because of the international sporting boycott due to apartheid.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] Invitations were given to Argentina, Fiji, Italy, Canada, Romania, Tonga, Japan, Zimbabwe and the United States.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] This left Western Samoa controversially excluded, despite their better playing standard than some of the teams invited.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The USSR were to be invited but they declined the invitation on political grounds, allegedly due to the continued IRFB membership of South Africa.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] There was no qualification process for the tournament.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The tournament witnessed a number of one-sided matches, with the seven IRFB members proving too strong for the other teams.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] Half of the 24 matches across the four pools saw one team score 40 or more points.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The tournament was seen as a major success and proved that the event was viable in the long term.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The tournament comprised the seven members of the IRFB, and nine teams invited by the IRFB; there was no qualification process for teams.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The inaugural World Cup was contested by 16 nations.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] There was no qualifying tournament to determine the participants; instead, the 16 nations were invited by the International Rugby Football Board to compete.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The simple 16-team pool/knock-out format was used with the teams divided into four pools of four, with each team playing the others in their pool once, for a total of three matches per team in the pool stage.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The runners-up of each pool faced the winners of a different pool in the quarter-finals.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] A standard single-elimination tournament followed, with the losers of the semi-finals contesting an additional play-off match to determine third place.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] A total of 32 matches (24 in the pool stage and eight in the knock-out stage) were played in the tournament over 29 days from 22 May to 20 June 1987.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was New Zealand's Grant Fox, who scored 126 points.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] Craig Green and John Kirwan scored the most tries, six in total.
[src:tonga/1987-rugby-world-cup] The event was broadcast in Australia by ABC and by TVNZ in New Zealand as host broadcasters supplying their pictures to broadcasters around the world and in the United Kingdom by the BBC and in Ireland by RTÉ.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The **1995 Rugby League World Cup** (also known as **Halifax Centenary World Cup** for sponsorship reasons) was the eleventh World Cup for mens national rugby league teams.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] It was held between 7–28 October and hosted by England and Wales and was won by Australia who beat England at Wembley Stadium, their eighth World Cup win and fifth in succession.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Organised to celebrate the sports centenary, ten nations were invited to participate.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The tournament had been preceded by doubts and pessimism; many feared that it would produce one-sided-matches that would be unattractive to supporters.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The forthcoming Super League war also hung over the tournament, with the Australian Rugby League refusing to select players who had signed for the rival competition.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Those fears proved unfounded, and the tournament was acclaimed a great success.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Although some early matches did prove as one-sided as feared, fans still flocked to see newer rugby league nations such as Fiji, Tonga, Western Samoa and South Africa.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Large home crowds for the group involving Wales proved particularly encouraging for the sport.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] For the 1995 tournament, a £10,000 cup was made by Tiffanys to celebrate the centenary of the game.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Ten teams competed in the Centenary World Cup: Australia, England, Fiji, France, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, South Africa, Tonga, Wales and Western Samoa.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] It was the first time since the 1975 World Series that England and Wales competed, rather than Great Britain.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Fiji, South Africa, Tonga and Western Samoa all made their World Cup débuts.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Scotland and Ireland took part in the Emerging Nations Tournament that was held alongside the World Cup.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Australia was missing some of their best players, a number of whom had been part of the 1994 Kangaroos squad, due to the Super League war and the ARL's refusal to select Super League-aligned players.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Australia's win in the end, with what many considered to be a second-string side, was seen as a blow to the Super League organisation, with which every other nation was aligned.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Canberra Raiders players Laurie Daley, Ricky Stuart, Bradley Clyde, Steve Walters and Brett Mullins, won a court order against the ARL making Super League players eligible for representative games.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Despite assurances from the ARL that all players were considered, only ARL loyal players were selected for the Kangaroos World Cup squad.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The games were played at various venues in England and Wales.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Wembley Stadium in London was the host stadium for the opening ceremony and match featuring hosts England and defending champions Australia.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Wembley, England's national stadium, would also host the Final of the tournament.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] England as expected defeated reigning European Champions Wales in their semi-final at Old Trafford.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The other Semi at Huddersfield almost produced a boil over.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] However, 20 minutes of extra time saw Australia skip away to a 30–20 win to book their place in the Final at Wembley.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The Australians had reached the final after a hard-fought 30–20 Semi-final win over New Zealand at the McAlpine Stadium which had gone into extra time after the score was locked at 20-all after 80 minutes.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Their opponents and tournament host England, had an easier time defeating Wales 25–10 in their semi at Old Trafford.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Even though they were favoured to win, Australia went into the final having lost three of their past four games at Wembley (the only win being the World Cup final of 1992), and had already lost the opening match of the tournament there to the English.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Also, due to the ARL's policy of not selecting Super League aligned players, the Kangaroos went into the game with 11 of their 17 players under the age of 24.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Although considered mostly a 'second string' team without the likes of Laurie Daley, Ricky Stuart, Andrew Ettingshausen, Steve Renouf, Steve Walters and Glenn Lazarus, most of the Kangaroos had played in the 3–0 whitewash of New Zealand in the Trans-Tasman series earlier in the year.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Kangaroos captain and five-eighth Brad Fittler and fullback Tim Brasher were the only members of Australia's 1992 World Cup final win over Great Britain at Wembley, with both players in the same positions as they had been three years previously.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] England's captain Shaun Edwards ruled himself out of the final with an infected knee.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Despite almost being ruled out of the tournament with pneumonia, St Helens centre Paul Newlove was selected by coach Phil Larder for starting line-up in the final.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Larder also handed the captaincy to veteran test forward Denis Betts.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] With the former Wigan back rower now playing for the Auckland Warriors in the Australian premiership, his selection as captain created history as he became the first player to captain England while not currently playing in the British competition.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] After winning in 1992, Australian coach Bob Fulton became just the second coach (after Harry Bath) to win two Rugby League World Cups.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] It was Fulton's 5th World Cup win after also winning in 1968, 1970 and 1975 as a player.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Coincidentally, Fulton's coach in the 1968 and 1970 World Cup finals was Harry Bath.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Status Quo performed the pre-match entertainment, performing When You Walk in the Room and Rockin' All Over the World.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] England won the coin toss and Australia's Andrew Johns kicked off the match.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] In England's first set with the ball Australia were penalised for their skipper Brad Fittler's high tackle on Andrew Farrell.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] From the resulting good field position England were able to force a line drop-out and get another set of six in Australia's half of the field.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] At the end of the set, Radlinski put up a high kick, which Australia's fullback Tim Brasher failed to secure and Australia were penalised for regathering the ball when off-side.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Bobbie Goulding kicked the penalty goal from fifteen metres out, giving his side a 2–0 lead.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] From Australia's resulting kick-off, the English players couldn't secure the ball and it was regathered by the Kangaroos deep in the opposition half.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] On the last tackle of the ensuing set, Johns at first receiver put a chip kick into the left-hand corner of England's in-goal area where winger Rod Wishart dived in and got a hand on it, giving Australia the first try of the match in the seventh minute.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Johns then converted the try from the touch-line and the Kangaroos were leading 6–2.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] A few minutes later England were penalised around the centre of the field and Johns attempted the kick at goal but missed.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] With the game now swinging from end to end, Johns conceded a penalty close to the goal posts and Goulding's kick bounced off the uprights but went in, so England were trailing 6–4 by the eighteenth minute.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] A few minutes later England conceded a penalty in front of their goal posts and Johns kicked Australia to an 8–4 lead.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] After a high shot from Andy Farrell on Mark Carroll, Johns kicked another penalty giving Australia a 10–4 lead at the 30-minute mark.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Just before the half-time break England conceded another penalty in the ruck but Johns' kick missed so the score remained unchanged at the break.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] After making their way into good attacking field position, England played the ball ten metres out from Australia's goal-line where centre Paul Newlove at dummy-half ran the ball at the defence forced his way through to score in the left corner.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The sideline conversion attempt by Goulding missed so England trailed 10–8 after five minutes of the second half.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Around the ten-minute mark the game was interrupted by a topless female streaker.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The play continued swinging from one end of the field to the other, with neither team able to capitalise on their scoring opportunities for the next twenty minutes.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Australian interchange player Jason Smith was blood binned and had to return to the bench.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] A few minutes later the Kangaroos had made their way deep into England's half when, on the last tackle, the ball was moved through the hands and eventually flicked passed back from Johns as he was being tackled to the feet of Brasher who kicked it ahead to the try-line.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Both fullbacks then scrambled to get to the ball and the referee ruled that Brasher had grounded it, awarding Australia a try.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Johns converted the try so Australia lead 16–8 with just over 10 minutes remaining.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] England forward Karl Harrison then had to come off the field with an injured arm.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] A few minutes from full-time Australian forward Mark Carroll was sent to the sin-bin for an infringement in the ruck.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] The remainder of the match extended into additional injury time but was played with no further points so Australia retained the World Cup with a 16–8 victory and their fifth consecutive world title.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] 21-year-old Andrew Johns was named man-of-the-match.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Kangaroos coach Bob Fulton had named the young half as the team hooker, and he did indeed pack into the scrums.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] However Johns played at halfback in general play with Geoff Toovey having the dummy-half duties, necessary because Toovey had actually injured his neck during the tournament and simply could not pack into the front row in the scrums.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] Following the match Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex presented Kangaroos captain Brad Fittler with the Cup and each of the players with medals.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] During the 1990 Kangaroo Tour, an 18-year-old Fittler had reportedly broken protocol when he had said *"G'day dude"* to Prince Edward's father, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh when the team had met the Duke as part of the tour.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-league-world-cup] History allegedly repeated itself as Fittler was heard to say *"Thanks dude"* to Prince Edward when receiving the World Cup on the Wembley balcony.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The **1995 Rugby World Cup** (Afrikaans: *Rugbywêreldbeker 1995*) was the third Rugby World Cup.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] It was hosted and won by South Africa, and was the first Rugby World Cup in which every match was held in one country.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The World Cup was the first major sporting event to take place in South Africa following the end of apartheid.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] It was also the first World Cup in which South Africa was allowed to compete; the International Rugby Football Board (IRFB, now World Rugby) had only readmitted South Africa to international rugby in 1992, following negotiations to end apartheid.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The World Cup was also the last major event of rugby union's amateur era; two months after the tournament, the IRFB opened the sport to professionalism.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] In the final, held at Ellis Park in Johannesburg on 24 June, South Africa defeated New Zealand 15–12, with Joel Stransky scoring a drop goal in extra time to win the match.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Following South Africa's victory, Nelson Mandela, the President of South Africa, wearing a Springboks rugby shirt and cap, presented the Webb Ellis Cup to the South African captain François Pienaar.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The eight quarter-finalists from the 1991 Rugby World Cup all received automatic entry, as did South Africa, as hosts.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The remaining seven of the 16 positions available in the tournament were filled by regional qualifiers.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The qualifying tournaments were broken up into regional associations: Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe and Oceania.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Côte d'Ivoire qualified through Africa, Japan through Asia, Argentina through the Americas, Italy, Romania and Wales through Europe, Tonga through Oceania.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The 1995 tournament was the first Rugby World Cup to be hosted by just one country, and thus, all the venues are within the one country.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] South Africa were given the rights to host the tournament in 1993, after a meeting between the IRB and both the government led by F.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] W. de Klerk and the African National Congress.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] In total, nine stadiums were used for the World Cup, most being owned by local municipalities, and the majority of the venues were upgraded prior to the tournament.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Six of the nine stadiums were South African Test grounds.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The four largest stadiums were used for the finals, with the final taking place at Johannesburg's Ellis Park.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] There were games originally scheduled to have been played in Brakpan, Germiston, Pietermaritzburg and Witbank, but these games were reallocated to other venues.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] This reduced the number of venues from 14 to 9.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The reasons cited for this change had to do with facilities for both the press and spectators, as well as the security.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The change in the itinerary occurred in January 1994.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Further changes occurred in April, so that evening games were played at stadiums with good floodlighting.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] It is also thought that Potchefstroom was an original venue.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tournament was contested by 16 nations using the same format that was used in 1987 and 1991 and in total 32 matches were played.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The competition began on 25 May, when the hosts South Africa defeated Australia 27–18 at Newlands in Cape Town.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tournament culminated with the final between South Africa and the All Blacks at Ellis Park in Johannesburg on 24 June.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] In total, the tournament ran for thirty days.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The nations were broken up into four pools of four, with each pool consisting of two teams that were automatically qualified and two that went through the qualifying tournaments.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Pool winners were drawn against opposite pool runners-up in the quarter-finals.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] For example, the winner of A faces the runner up of B, and the winner of B face the runner-up of A.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The whole finals stage adopts a knock-out format, and the winners of the quarter-finals advance to the semi-finals, where winner 1 faces winner 2, and winner 3 faces winner 4.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The winners advance to the final, and the losers contest a third/fourth place play-off two days before the final.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] A total of 32 matches (24 pool stage & 8 knock-out) were played throughout the tournament over 30 days from 25 May to 24 June 1995.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Three minutes into the match between Ivory Coast and Tonga, the Ivorian winger Max Brito was crushed beneath several other players, leaving him paralysed below the neck.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The final was contested by New Zealand and hosts South Africa.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Both nations finished undefeated at the top of their pools.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] South Africa defeated Western Samoa in the quarter-finals, and then France in the semi-finals to reach the final; New Zealand defeated Scotland in the quarter-finals, and England in the semi-finals, a game in which Jonah Lomu famously scored four tries for the All Blacks.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The final was played at Ellis Park in Johannesburg and refereed by Ed Morrison of England.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] To this point, New Zealand had led the tournament in production, outscoring their opponents 315–104, while South Africa had outscored their opponents 129–55.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tight Springbok defence would keep the high scoring All Blacks in check – particularly Jonah Lomu and Marc Ellis, who had already scored a then World Cup record seven tries each in the tournament – with neither team scoring a try in the match.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] South Africa led 9–6 at half time, and New Zealand levelled the scores at 9–9 with a drop goal in the second half.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Though Andrew Mehrtens almost kicked a late drop goal for the All Blacks, the score remained tied at full-time, forcing the game into extra time.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Both teams scored penalty goals in the first half of extra time, but Joel Stransky then scored a drop goal to win the final for South Africa.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] An iconic moment occurred after the game when Nelson Mandela, wearing a Springbok rugby jersey and cap, presented the Webb Ellis Cup to South African captain François Pienaar.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The moment is thought by some to be one of the most famous finals of any sport.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was France's Thierry Lacroix, who scored 112 points.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Marc Ellis and Jonah Lomu, both of New Zealand, scored the most tries, with seven each.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The event was broadcast in Australia by Network Ten and in the United Kingdom by ITV.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] The South African Mint issued a one-ounce gold proof "Protea" coin with a total mintage of 406 pieces to commemorate the event being hosted by South Africa.
[src:tonga/1995-rugby-world-cup] Mandela and Pienaar's involvement in the World Cup is the subject of the John Carlin book *Playing the Enemy: Nelson Mandela and the Game That Made a Nation*, its 2009 film adaptation *Invictus*, and the ESPN TV documentary *The 16th Man* in 2010.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The **1996 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the XXVI Olympiad**, also known as **Atlanta 1996** and commonly referred to as the **Centennial Olympic Games**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 19 to August 4, 1996, in Atlanta, Georgia, United States.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] These were the fourth Summer Olympics to be hosted by the United States, making it the first country to have three different cities host the Summer Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] It also marked the 100th anniversary of the 1896 Summer Olympics in Athens, the inaugural edition of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] These were also the first Summer Olympics to be held in a different year than the Winter Olympics since the Winter Olympics commenced in 1924, as part of a new IOC practice implemented in 1994 to hold the Summer and Winter Games in alternating, even-numbered years.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Games were the first of the two consecutive Summer Olympics to be held in a predominantly English-speaking country, preceding the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] These were also the last Summer Olympics to be held in North America until 2028, when Los Angeles will host the games for the third time.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] A total of 24 countries made their Summer Olympic debuts in Atlanta, including 11 former Soviet republics participating for the first time as independent nations.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] With a total of 101 medals, the United States topped both the gold and overall medal count for the first time since 1984 (and for the first time since 1968 in a non-boycotted Summer Olympics), also winning the most gold (44) and silver (32) medals out of all the participating nations.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Games were marred by violence on July 27, 1996, when a pipe bomb was detonated at Centennial Olympic Park (which had been built to serve as a public focal point for the festivities), killing two and injuring 111.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Years later, Eric Rudolph confessed to the bombing and a series of related terrorist attacks, and was sentenced to life in prison.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Nonetheless, the 1996 Olympics turned a profit, helped by record revenue from sponsorship deals and broadcast rights, and a reliance on private funding, among other factors.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] There were 8.3 million tickets sold for events at this Olympics, a record broken only in 2024.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] There was some criticism of the perceived over-commercialization of the Games, with other issues raised by European officials, such as the availability of food and transport.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta was selected on September 18, 1990, in Tokyo, Japan, over Athens, Belgrade, Manchester, Melbourne, and Toronto at the 96th IOC Session.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The city entered the competition as a dark horse, being up against stiff competition.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The US media also criticized Atlanta as a second-tier city and complained of Georgia's Confederate history.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] However, the IOC Evaluation Commission ranked Atlanta's infrastructure and facilities the highest, while IOC members said that it could guarantee large television revenues similar to the success of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, the most recent Olympics in the United States.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Additionally, former US ambassador to the UN and Atlanta mayor Andrew Young touted Atlanta's civil rights history and reputation for racial harmony.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Young also wanted to showcase a reformed American South.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The strong economy of Atlanta and improved race relations in the South helped to impress the IOC officials.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Coca-Cola, a long-standing partner of the Olympics, was also a strong advocate to bring the Games to its hometown.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) also proposed a substantial revenue-sharing with the IOC, USOC, and other NOCs.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] This would be Toronto's fourth failed attempt since 1960 (tried in 1960, 1964, and 1976, but was defeated by Rome, Tokyo and Montreal).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Greece, the home of the ancient and first modern Olympics, was considered by many observers the "natural choice" for the Centennial Games, due to its "divine right" in history.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Athens bid chairman Spyros Metaxas gave repeated warnings to the IOC and demanded to give them the games to mark the centennial, saying "You don't hold a 100th birthday in someone else's home.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] However, the Athens bid was described as "arrogant and poorly prepared," being regarded as "not being up to the task of coping with the modern and risk-prone extravaganza" of the current Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The total cost of the 1996 Summer Olympics was estimated to be around US$1.7 billion.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] In total, the Games turned a profit of $19 million.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The cost for Atlanta 1996 compares with costs of $4.6 billion for Rio 2016, $40–44 billion for Beijing 2008, and $51 billion for Sochi 2014 Winter Olympics (the most expensive Olympic Games without differentiating between summer and winter in history).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is $5.2 billion.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] ACOG budgeted $32.7 million for Atlanta Police Department and Georgia Department of Public Safety services during the games. $70 million in funding came from the U.S. federal government for additional services, including 500 additional federal agents.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Transportation relied heavily on an expanded MARTA rail and 3,000 additional buses borrowed from nationwide transit agencies.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Ticketed events came with free public transportation.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Shuttles were provided for VIPs, athletes and olympic officials.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] These shuttles connected remote Park 'N Ride lots, central terminals, and specific competition venues.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The city implemented new High-Occupancy Vehicle lanes on I-75 and I-85 highways and coordinated traffic from a centralized Traffic Management Center to handle the daily crowds that often exceeded 500,000 people.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The games were challenged by driver shortages, route navigation errors, and logistical delays.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Events of the 1996 Games were held in a completely decentralized way using mostly existing facilities that were not built for the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Most of the events were held in the so-called Olympic Ring, a 3 mi (4.8 km) circle from the center of Atlanta.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Others were held at Stone Mountain, about 20 miles (32 km) outside of the city.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] In many cases, it was decided to remove events from the Atlanta Metropolitan Region to save money, while in others the calendar was a difficulty, as was the case with association football (soccer) which ended up having its host cities spread across the Southeastern United States region.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] During early planning stages in 1992, Payne and the ACOG wanted a golf event to be held at Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Initially, Augusta agreed, but protests from civil rights leaders and politicians against the club's strict admission policies led to the collapse of the idea.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympic Arts Festival offered 200 ticketed events, including more than 20 exhibitions in local institutions, museums, and gallery spaces.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] More than 3,000 artists participated during the two weeks of the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] There were numerous free events including a daily series of music at Centennial Olympic Park, called "Southern Crossroads".
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] In 1994, African-American artist Kevin Cole was commissioned to create the Coca-Cola Centennial Olympic Wall, and the 15-story mural took two years to complete.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympiad's official theme, "Summon the Heroes", was written by John Williams, making it the third Olympiad at that point for which he had composed (official composer in 1984, NBC's coverage composer in 1988).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony featured Céline Dion singing "The Power of the Dream", the theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony featured Gloria Estefan singing "Reach", the official theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The torch relay was run from April 27 to July 19, leading up to the Games in Atlanta.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The route covered 26,875 kilometers (16,699 mi) across the United States.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The relay involved over 12,000 torchbearers, including Muhammad Ali, who was chosen to ignite the flame at the opening ceremony.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] 8.32 million tickets were sold, a record recently broken by Paris 2024.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Ticket sales brought in $420 million for the ACOG, 1/4 of its operating budget.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The "Look of the Games" design for Atlanta 1996 was named "Quilt of Leaves".
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The graphic identity featured a quilting leaf pattern.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Representing a city coming together—with laurel leaves.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The "Quilt of Leaves" theme appeared across official venues, signage, tickets, credentials, and even physically minted into the back of the Atlanta 1996 Olympic Medals.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The logo was designed by Landor Associates, it featured the Olympic flame and stars in five vibrant colors above the number 100.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The base resembled a classical Greek column to celebrate the centennial of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The main backdrop color was: *Georgia forest green*.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] It represented green laurels branches worn by winners in ancient Greece as well as Atlanta being nicknamed "city of trees".
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The colors palette featured *khaki gold*, *tomato orange*, *magenta*, *blue* and *purple*.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta's Olympic slogan "Come Celebrate Our Dream" was written by Jack Arogeti, a managing director at McCann-Erickson in Atlanta at the time.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The slogan was selected from more than 5,000 submitted by the public to the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Izzy was an abstract, amorphous tech-generated blue fantasy figure character wearing white gloves and red shoes.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] In contrast to the standing tradition of mascots of national or regional significance to the city hosting.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Created by John Ryan, an Atlanta animator from the DESIGNefx firm.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] A video game featuring the Games' mascot, *Izzy's Quest for the Olympic Rings*, was also released.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Summer Olympics relied heavily on commercial sponsorship, 111 total domestic corporate partners.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Company was the exclusive provider of soft drinks at Olympics venues, and built an attraction known as Coca-Cola Olympic City for the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] As part of a sponsorship agreement with Columbia TriStar Television, the syndicated game shows *Jeopardy!* and *Wheel of Fortune* both produced episodes with Olympics tie-ins (including branded memorabilia and contests) for broadcast between April and July 1996.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] These included a *Jeopardy!* international tournament, and three weeks of *Wheel of Fortune* episodes filmed on-location at Atlanta's Fox Theatre.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta organizing committee threatened legal actions against advertisers whose marketing implied an official association with the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Several non-sponsors set up marketing activities in areas near venues, such as Samsung (competing with Motorola), which ambushed the Games with its "96 Expo".
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The city of Atlanta had also licensed street vendors to sell products from competitors to Olympic sponsors.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Nike also opened a pop-up store known as the Nike Center near the Athletes' Village, which distributed Nike-branded flags to visitors (presumably to be used at events).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] IOC marketing director Michael Payne expressed concern for the campaign, believing that athletes could perceive them as being an insult to their accomplishments.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Payne and the United States Olympic Committee's marketing director, John Krimsky, met with Howard Slusher, a subordinate of Nike co-founder Phil Knight.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Faced with these threats, Nike agreed to retract most of its negative advertising and public relations stunts.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] A total of 197 nations, all of the then-existing and recognized National Olympic Committees, were represented at the 1996 Games, and the combined total of athletes was about 10,318.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Twenty-four countries made their Olympic debut this year, including eleven of the ex-Soviet countries that competed as part of the Unified Team in 1992.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Russia participated in the Summer Olympics separately from the other countries of the former Soviet Union for the first time since 1912 (when it was the Russian Empire).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Russia had been a member of the Unified Team at the 1992 Summer Olympics together with 11 post-Soviet states.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia competed as *Yugoslavia*.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] After missing the 1992 Summer Games Afghanistan and Cambodia returned to send delegations to Atlanta.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 14 countries making their Olympic debut were: Azerbaijan, Burundi, Cape Verde, Comoros, Dominica, Guinea-Bissau, Macedonia, Nauru, Palestinian Authority, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Saint Lucia, São Tomé and Príncipe, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The ten countries making their Summer Olympic debut (after competing at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer) were: Armenia, Belarus, Czech Republic, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Slovakia, Ukraine and Uzbekistan.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Czech Republic and Slovakia attended the games as independent nations for the first time since the breakup of Czechoslovakia, while the rest of the nations that made their Summer Olympic debut were formerly part of the Soviet Union.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] 10,339 athletes from 197 NOCs participated in the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The ceremony began with a 60-second countdown, which included footage from all of the previous Olympic Games at twenty-two seconds.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] There was then a flashback to the closing ceremony of the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, showing the then president of the IOC, Juan Antonio Samaranch, inviting the athletes to compete in Atlanta in 1996.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Then, spirits ascended in the northwest corner of the stadium, each representing one of the colors in the Olympic rings.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The spirits called the tribes of the world which, after mixed percussion, formed the Olympic rings while the youth of Atlanta formed the number 100.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Famed film score composer John Williams wrote the official overture for the 1996 Olympics, called "Summon the Heroes"; this was his second overture for Olympic games, the first being "Olympic Fanfare and Theme" written for the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Céline Dion performed David Foster's official 1996 Olympics song "The Power of the Dream", accompanied by Foster on the piano, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and the Centennial Choir (comprising Morehouse College Glee Club, Spelman College Glee Club and the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Chorus).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Gladys Knight sang Georgia's official state song, "Georgia on My Mind".
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] There was another showcase entitled "Summertime" which focused on Atlanta and the Old South, emphasizing its beauty, spirit, music, history, culture, and rebirth after the American Civil War.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The ceremony also featured a memorable dance tribute to the athletes and to the goddesses of victory of the ancient Greek Olympics, using silhouette imagery.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The accompanying music, "The Tradition of the Games", was composed by Basil Poledouris.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Muhammad Ali lit the Olympic cauldron and later received a replacement gold medal for his boxing victory in the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] For the torch ceremony, more than 10,000 Olympic torches were manufactured by the American Meter Company, electroplated by Klein Plating Works, and polished by Erie Plating Company.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Each torch weighed about 3.5 pounds (1.6 kg) and was made primarily of aluminum, with a Georgia pecan wood handle and gold ornamentation.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The city of Savannah, Georgia, host of the yachting events, also held their own opening ceremony on the first day of their competitions.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The event was headlined by a performance by country musician Trisha Yearwood.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Summer Olympic program featured 271 events in 26 sports.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Softball, beach volleyball and mountain biking debuted on the Olympic program, together with women's football, lightweight events in rowing, Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay in swimming, the Women's épée in fencing and the group all-around event in rhythmic gymnastics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1996 Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Domestic network NBC bought the broadcasting rights for US$456 million.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The European Broadcasting Union paid US$240 million.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympics were marred by the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, which occurred on July 27.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Security guard Richard Jewell discovered the pipe bomb and immediately notified law enforcement, helping to evacuate as many people as possible from the area before it exploded.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Although Jewell's quick actions are credited for saving many lives, the bombing killed spectator Alice Hawthorne, wounded 111 others, and caused the death of Melih Uzunyol by a heart attack.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Jewell was later considered a suspect in the bombing but was never charged, and he was cleared in October 1996.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Fugitive Eric Rudolph was arrested in May 2003 and charged with the Olympic Park bombing as well as the bombings of two abortion clinics and a gay nightclub.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Preparations for the Olympics lasted more than seven years and had an economic impact of at least US$5.14 billion.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Over two million visitors came to Atlanta, and approximately 3.5 billion people around the world watched at least some of the events on television.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Although marred by the tragedy of the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, the Games were a financial success, due in part to TV rights contracts and sponsorships at record levels.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta also set a new record for the most tickets sold at a single Games (8.3 million), and held it until 2024.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Beyond international recognition, the Games resulted in many modern infrastructure improvements.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The mid-rise dormitories built for the Olympic Village, which became the first residential housing for Georgia State University (Georgia State Village), are now used by the Georgia Institute of Technology (North Avenue Apartments).
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] As designed, the Centennial Olympic Stadium was converted into Turner Field after the Paralympics, which became the home of the Atlanta Braves Major League Baseball team from 1997 to 2016.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Braves' former home, Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium, was demolished in 1997 and the site became a parking lot for Turner Field; the Omni Coliseum was demolished the same year to make way for State Farm Arena.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The city's permanent memorial to the 1996 Olympics is Centennial Olympic Park, which was built as a focal point for the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The park initiated a revitalization of the surrounding area and now serves as the hub for Atlanta's tourism district.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] In November 2016, a commemorative plaque was unveiled for Centennial Olympic Park to honor the 20th anniversary of the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Following the Braves' departure from Turner Field to Truist Park in 2017, Georgia State University acquired the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding parking lots.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] It reconfigured the stadium for a second time into Center Parc Stadium for its college football team.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympic cauldron was originally built and placed at the intersection of Fulton Street and Capitol Avenue, near the Centennial Olympic Stadium.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] After the Paralympics, in order to make room for the stadium conversion, the Olympic cauldron was moved (except its ramp, which was demolished) to the intersection of Capitol Avenue and Fulton Street in 1997, where it has stayed since.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Since Georgia State University's acquisition of the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding lots, there has been proposals and growing calls to move the Olympic cauldron to Centennial Olympic Park.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympic cauldron was re-lit in February 2020 for the 2020 U.S.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympics are the most recent edition of the Summer Olympics to be held in the United States.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will host the 2028 Summer Olympics, 32 years after the Games were held in Atlanta.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] In 1997, Athens was awarded the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Along with addressing the shortcomings of its 1996 bid, it was lauded for its efforts to promote the traditional values of the Olympic Games, which some IOC observers felt had been lost due to the over-commercialization of the 1996 Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] However, the 2004 Games heavily relied on public funding and eventually failed to make a profit, which some have claimed contributed to the financial crisis in Greece.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The financial struggles faced by many later Games, such as the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin and the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, have caused some to offer more positive reappraisals of the management of the 1996 Summer Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] Former JPMorgan Chase president (and torchbearer) Kabir Sehgal noted that in contrast to many later Olympics, those of 1996 were financially viable, had a positive economic impact on the city, and most of the facilities constructed continued to be used after the Games.
[src:tonga/1996-summer-olympics] The 2028 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles will rely almost entirely on private funding, with the city of Los Angeles and state of California each intending to provide up to $250 million in funding in the event of shortfalls, and the U.S. federal government providing funding solely for security.
[src:tonga/to] The government of Tonga sells domains in its ccTLD to any interested party.
[src:tonga/to] The .to ccTLD is administered by the Tonga Network Information Center (Tonic).
[src:tonga/to] The .to top-level domain was widely commercialized in 1997 by the San Francisco company Tonic Corp.
[src:tonga/to] (founded by Eric Gullichsen and Eric Lyons) which would sell domains at $100 each.
[src:tonga/to] They operated with the approval of Prince Siaosi, the then-Crown Prince of Tonga in response to controversy over Network Solutions, LLC's .to ccTLD registration practices.
[src:tonga/to] Domain requests were processed by the Tongan consulate in San Francisco.
[src:tonga/to] The top-level domain *to* itself had an A record and an HTTP server since at least 1998.
[src:tonga/to] "T.O." is also a common nickname for Toronto, and is used as a city domain there and elsewhere in cities like Torino (Turin), Italy.
[src:tonga/to] It is also a domain hack in Slavic languages (*to* meaning *it* or *that*) – such as the uploading service uloz.to ("ulož to" means "save it" in Czech and Slovak).
[src:tonga/to] All normal DNS operations are available for .to websites and registered sites are not required to display ads on behalf of the registrar.
[src:tonga/to] Some domains such as .edu.to or .gov.to are restricted to legitimate Tongan institutions.
[src:tonga/to] At this moment businesses registered in Tonga can also get free domains.
[src:tonga/to] People who sell on .to domains can claim a commission.
[src:tonga/to] .to provides a WHOIS service at `whois.tonicregistry.to`.
[src:tonga/to] The .to registry allows the creation of emoji domain names.
[src:tonga/to] A former .to registrar, Register.TO, did support the search and registration of .to emoji domain names.
[src:tonga/to] Register.TO is no longer an authorized registrar for .to domain names, following the death of its owner in early 2023 as stated by the NIC of Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga was first inhabited roughly 2,500 years ago by people who were a part of the Lapita culture, Polynesian settlers who gradually evolved a distinct and strong ethnic identity, language, and culture as the Tongan people.
[src:tonga/tonga] They quickly established a powerful footing across the South Pacific, and this period of Tongan expansionism and colonization is known as the Tuʻi Tonga Empire.
[src:tonga/tonga] From the rule of the first Tongan king, ʻAhoʻeitu, Tonga grew into a regional power.
[src:tonga/tonga] It was a thalassocracy that conquered and controlled unprecedented swathes of the Pacific, from parts of the Solomon Islands and the whole of New Caledonia and Fiji in the west to Samoa and Niue and even as far as parts of modern-day French Polynesia in the east.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tuʻi Tonga became renowned for its economic, ethnic, and cultural influence over the Pacific, which remained strong even after the Samoan revolution of the thirteenth century and Europeans' discovery of the islands in 1616.
[src:tonga/tonga] From 1900 to 1970, Tonga had British protected-state status.
[src:tonga/tonga] The United Kingdom looked after Tonga's foreign affairs under a Treaty of Friendship, but Tonga never relinquished its sovereignty to any foreign power.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2010, Tonga took a decisive step away from its traditional absolute monarchy and became a semi-constitutional monarchy, after legislative reforms paved the way for its first partial representative elections.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga is a member of the Commonwealth of Nations, the United Nations, the Pacific Islands Forum, and the Alliance of Small Island States.
[src:tonga/tonga] In many Polynesian languages, including Tongan, the word *tonga* (Tongan: [ˈtoŋa]), comes from *fakatonga*, which means 'southwards', and the archipelago is so named because it is the southernmost group among the island groups of western Polynesia.
[src:tonga/tonga] The word *tonga* is cognate to the Hawaiian word *kona* meaning 'leeward', which is the origin of the name for the Kona District in Hawaiʻi.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga became known in the West as the "Friendly Islands" because of the congenial reception accorded to Captain James Cook on his first visit in 1773.
[src:tonga/tonga] He arrived at the time of the annual *ʻinasi* festival, which centres on the donation of the First Fruits to the Tuʻi Tonga (the islands' monarch), so he received an invitation to the festivities.
[src:tonga/tonga] Ironically, according to the writer William Mariner, the political leaders actually wanted to kill Cook during the gathering, but did not go through with it because they could not agree on a plan of action for accomplishing it.
[src:tonga/tonga] According to Tongan mythology, the demigod Maui drew up a group of islands from the ocean, first appearing Tongatapu, the Ha'apai Islands and Vava'u, integrating into what became modern-day Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] An Austronesian-speaking group linked to what archaeologists call the Lapita culture covered from Island Melanesia to Samoa, and then on to inhabit Tonga sometime between 1500 and 1000 BC.
[src:tonga/tonga] Scholars still debate exactly when Tonga was first settled, but thorium dating confirms that settlers had arrived in the earliest known inhabited town, Nukuleka, by 888 BC, ± 8 years.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's precontact history was shared via oral history, which was passed down from generation to generation.
[src:tonga/tonga] By the 12th century, Tongans and the Tongan monarch, the Tuʻi Tonga, had acquired a reputation across the central Pacific – from Niue, Samoa, Rotuma, Wallis and Futuna, New Caledonia to Tikopia, leading some historians to speak of a Tuʻi Tonga Empire having existed during that period.
[src:tonga/tonga] Civil wars are known to have occurred in Tonga in the 15th and 17th centuries.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Tongan people first encountered Europeans in 1616, when the Dutch vessel *Eendracht*, captained by Willem Schouten, made a short visit to the islands for the purpose of engaging in trade.
[src:tonga/tonga] Later, other Dutch explorers arrived, including Jacob Le Maire (who visited the northern island of Niuatoputapu); and Abel Tasman (who visited Tongatapu and Haʻapai) in 1643.
[src:tonga/tonga] Whaling vessels were among the earliest regular Western visitors.
[src:tonga/tonga] The first of these on record is the *Ann and Hope*, which was reported to have been seen among the islands of Tonga in June 1799.
[src:tonga/tonga] The last known whaling visitor was the *Albatross* in 1899.
[src:tonga/tonga] That ship arrived in Tonga seeking a resupply of water, food, and wood.
[src:tonga/tonga] The islands most regularly visited by Westerners were Ata, 'Eua, Ha'apai, Tongatapu, and Vava'u.
[src:tonga/tonga] Sometimes, Tongan men were recruited to serve as crewmen on these vessels.
[src:tonga/tonga] The United States Exploring Expedition visited Tonga in 1840.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 1845, an ambitious young Tongan warrior, strategist, and orator named Tāufaʻāhau united Tonga into a kingdom.
[src:tonga/tonga] He held the chiefly title of Tuʻi Kanokupolu, but had been baptised by Methodist missionaries with the name *Siaosi* ("George") in 1831.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 1875, with the help of missionary Shirley Waldemar Baker, he declared Tonga a constitutional monarchy, formally adopted the Western royal style, emancipated the "serfs", enshrined a code of law, land tenure, and freedom of the press, and limited the power of the chiefs.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga became a protected state under a Treaty of Friendship with Britain on 18 May 1900, when European settlers and rival Tongan chiefs unsuccessfully tried to oust the man who had succeeded Tāufaʻāhau as king.
[src:tonga/tonga] The treaty posted no higher permanent representative on Tonga than a British consul (1901–1970).
[src:tonga/tonga] Under British protection, Tonga maintained its sovereignty and remained the only Pacific nation to retain its monarchical government.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Tongan monarchy has an uninterrupted succession of hereditary rulers from a single family.
[src:tonga/tonga] The 1918 flu pandemic, brought to Tonga by a ship from New Zealand, killed 1,800 Tongans, a mortality rate of about 8%.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Treaty of Friendship and Tonga's protection status ended in 1970 under arrangements that had been established by Tonga's Queen Salote Tupou III before her death in 1965.
[src:tonga/tonga] Owing to its British ties, Tonga joined the Commonwealth in 1970 (atypically as a country that had its own monarch, rather than having the United Kingdom's monarch, along with Malaysia, Brunei, Lesotho, and Eswatini).
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga became a member of the United Nations in September 1999.
[src:tonga/tonga] While exposed to colonial pressures, Tonga has always governed itself, which makes it unique in the Pacific.
[src:tonga/tonga] In January 2022, the Hunga Tonga–Hunga Haʻapai volcano, 65 km (40 mi; 35 nmi) north of the main island of Tongatapu, erupted, causing a tsunami which inundated parts of the archipelago, including the capital Nukuʻalofa.
[src:tonga/tonga] Comparable to the size of the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa, the Hunga volcano produced an atmospheric explosion never before documented in the modern geophysical record (not including man-made explosions).
[src:tonga/tonga] The eruption affected the kingdom heavily, cutting off most communications and killing four people in Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] In Peru, two women drowned due to abnormal tsunami waves.
[src:tonga/tonga] It took around five weeks to repair a submarine fiber optic cable used in the Tonga Cable System for internet and telephone connectivity.
[src:tonga/tonga] Located in Oceania, Tonga is an archipelago in the South Pacific Ocean, directly south of Samoa and about two-thirds of the way from Hawaiʻi to New Zealand.
[src:tonga/tonga] Its 171 islands, 45 of them inhabited, are divided into three main groups – Vava'u, Ha'apai, and Tongatapu – and cover an 800-kilometre (500-mile; 430-nautical-mile)-long north–south line.
[src:tonga/tonga] The largest island, Tongatapu, on which the capital city of Nukuʻalofa is located, covers 257 square kilometres (99 sq mi).
[src:tonga/tonga] Geologically, the Tongan islands are of two types: most have a limestone base formed from uplifted coral formations; others consist of limestone overlaying a volcanic base.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga has a tropical rainforest climate (*Af*) with a distinct warm period (December–April), during which the temperatures rise above 32 °C (89.6 °F), and a cooler period (May–November), with temperatures rarely rising above 27 °C (80.6 °F).
[src:tonga/tonga] The temperature and rainfall range from 23 °C (73.4 °F) and 1,700 mm (66.9 in) on Tongatapu in the south to 27 °C (80.6 °F) and 2,970 mm (116.9 in) on the more northerly islands closer to the Equator.
[src:tonga/tonga] The average wettest period is around March, with on average 263 mm (10.4 in).
[src:tonga/tonga] The highest temperature recorded in Tonga was 35 °C (95 °F) on 11 February 1979 in Vava'u.
[src:tonga/tonga] The coldest temperature recorded in Tonga was 8.7 °C (47.7 °F) on 8 September 1994 in Fua'amotu.
[src:tonga/tonga] Temperatures of 15 °C (59 °F) or lower are usually measured in the dry season and are more frequent in southern Tonga than in the northern islands.
[src:tonga/tonga] The tropical cyclone season currently runs from 1 November to 30 April, though tropical cyclones can form and affect Tonga outside of the season.
[src:tonga/tonga] According to the WorldRiskReport 2021, Tonga ranks third among the countries with the highest disaster risk worldwide – mainly due to the country's exposure to multiple natural hazards.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga contains the Tongan tropical moist forests terrestrial ecoregion.
[src:tonga/tonga] In Tonga, dating back to Tongan legend, flying bats are considered sacred and are the property of the monarchy.
[src:tonga/tonga] Thus, they are protected and cannot be harmed or hunted.
[src:tonga/tonga] As a result, flying fox bats have thrived in many of the islands of Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] The bird life of Tonga includes a total of 73 species, of which two are endemic, the Tongan whistler and the Tongan megapode.
[src:tonga/tonga] Five species have been introduced by humans, and eight are rare or accidental.
[src:tonga/tonga] It is the only extant indigenous monarchy in the Pacific islands (see also Hawaiʻi).
[src:tonga/tonga] Reverence for the monarch replaces that held in earlier centuries for the sacred paramount chief, the Tuʻi Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Criticism of the monarch is held to be contrary to Tongan culture and etiquette.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga provides for its citizens a free and mandatory education for all, secondary education with only nominal fees, and foreign-funded scholarships for postsecondary education.
[src:tonga/tonga] The pro-democracy movement in Tonga promotes reforms, including better representation in the Parliament for the majority of commoners, and better accountability in matters of state.
[src:tonga/tonga] An overthrow of the monarchy is not part of the movement, and the institution of monarchy continues to hold popular support, even while reforms are advocated.
[src:tonga/tonga] Until recently, the governance issue was generally ignored by the leaders of other countries, but major aid donors and neighbours New Zealand and Australia are now expressing concerns about some Tongan government actions.
[src:tonga/tonga] Male homosexuality is illegal in Tonga, with a maximum penalty of 10 years' imprisonment, but the law is not enforced.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tongans have universal access to a national health care system.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Constitution of Tonga protects land ownership; land cannot be sold to foreigners (although it may be leased).
[src:tonga/tonga] King Tāufaʻāhau Tupou IV and his government made some problematic economic decisions and were accused by democracy activists, including former prime minister ʻAkilisi Pōhiva, of wasting millions of dollars on unwise investments.
[src:tonga/tonga] The king proved vulnerable to speculators with big promises and lost reportedly US$26 million to Jesse Bogdonoff, a financial adviser who called himself the king's court jester.
[src:tonga/tonga] The police imprisoned pro-democracy leaders, and the government repeatedly confiscated the newspaper *The Tongan Times* (printed in New Zealand and sold in Tonga) because the editor had been vocally critical of the king's mistakes.
[src:tonga/tonga] Notably, the *Keleʻa*, produced specifically to critique the government and printed in Tonga by pro-democracy leader ʻAkilisi Pōhiva, was not banned during that time.
[src:tonga/tonga] Pōhiva, however, had been subjected to harassment in the form of barratry (frequent lawsuits).
[src:tonga/tonga] In mid-2003, the government passed a radical constitutional amendment to "Tonganize" the press, by licensing and limiting freedom of the press, so as to protect the image of the monarchy.
[src:tonga/tonga] The amendment was defended by the government and by royalists on the basis of traditional cultural values.
[src:tonga/tonga] Licensure criteria include 80% ownership by Tongans living in the country.
[src:tonga/tonga] As of February 2004, those papers denied licenses under the new act included the *Taimi ʻo Tonga* (*Tongan Times*), the *Keleʻa*, and the *Matangi Tonga* – while those permitted licenses were uniformly church-based or pro-government.
[src:tonga/tonga] The latter was supported by some 160 signatures, including seven of the nine elected "People's Representatives".
[src:tonga/tonga] The then–Crown Prince Tupoutoʻa and Pilolevu, the Princess Royal, remained generally silent on the issue.
[src:tonga/tonga] In total, the changes threatened to destabilise the polity, fragment support for the status quo, and place further pressure on the monarchy.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2005, the government spent several weeks negotiating with striking civil-service workers before reaching a settlement.
[src:tonga/tonga] The civil unrest that ensued was not limited to Tonga; protests outside the King's New Zealand residence made headlines.
[src:tonga/tonga] Prime Minister Prince ʻAhoʻeitu ʻUnuakiʻotonga Tukuʻaho (Lavaka Ata ʻUlukālala) (now King Tupou VI) resigned suddenly on 11 February 2006 and also gave up his other cabinet portfolios.
[src:tonga/tonga] The elected minister of labour, Feleti Sevele, replaced him in the interim.
[src:tonga/tonga] On 5 July 2006, a driver in Menlo Park, California, caused the deaths of Prince Tuʻipelehake ʻUluvalu, his wife, and their driver.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tuʻipelehake, 55, was the cochairman of the constitutional reform commission and a nephew of the king.
[src:tonga/tonga] The public expected some changes when George Tupou V succeeded his father in September 2006.
[src:tonga/tonga] On 16 November 2006, rioting broke out in the capital city of Nukuʻalofa when it seemed that the parliament would adjourn for the year without having made any advances in increasing democracy in government.
[src:tonga/tonga] Pro-democracy activists burned and looted shops, offices, and government buildings.
[src:tonga/tonga] As a result, more than 60% of the downtown area was destroyed and as many as six people died.
[src:tonga/tonga] The disturbances were ended by action from Tongan Security Forces and troops from New Zealand-led Joint Task Force.
[src:tonga/tonga] On 29 July 2008, the Palace announced that King George Tupou V would relinquish much of his power and would surrender his role in day-to-day governmental affairs to the Prime Minister.
[src:tonga/tonga] On 15 March 2012, King George Tupou V contracted pneumonia and was brought to Queen Mary Hospital in Hong Kong.
[src:tonga/tonga] His health deteriorated significantly shortly thereafter, and he died at 3:15 pm on 18 March 2012.
[src:tonga/tonga] He was succeeded by his brother Tupou VI, who was crowned on 4 July 2015.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's foreign policy as of January 2009 was described by Matangi Tonga as "Look East" – specifically, as establishing closer diplomatic and economic relations with Asia (which actually lies to the north-west of the Pacific kingdom).
[src:tonga/tonga] As of 2021, China has attained great influence in Tonga, financing infrastructure projects, including a new royal palace and holding two thirds of the country's foreign debt.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga retains cordial relations with the United States.
[src:tonga/tonga] Although it remains on good terms with the United Kingdom, the two countries do not maintain particularly close relations.
[src:tonga/tonga] The United Kingdom closed its High Commission in Tonga in 2006, although it was re-established in January 2020 after a 14-year absence.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's relations with Oceania's regional powers, Australia and New Zealand, are good.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga maintains strong regional ties in the Pacific.
[src:tonga/tonga] It is a full member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the South Pacific Applied Geoscience Commission, the South Pacific Tourism Organisation, the Pacific Regional Environment Programme, and the Secretariat of the Pacific Community.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Tongan government supported the American "coalition of the willing" action in Iraq and deployed more than 40 soldiers (as part of an American force) in late 2004.
[src:tonga/tonga] The contingent returned home on 17 December 2004.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2007, a second contingent went to Iraq, and two more were sent during 2008 as part of continued support for the coalition.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tongan involvement concluded at the end of 2008 with no reported loss of life.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2010, Brigadier General Tauʻaika ʻUtaʻatu, commander of the His Majesty's Armed Forces, signed an agreement in London committing a minimum of 200 troops to co-operate with Britain's International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan.
[src:tonga/tonga] The task was completed in April 2014, and the UK presented Operational Service Medals to each of the soldiers involved during a parade held in Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga has contributed troops and police to the Bougainville conflict in Papua-New Guinea and to the Australian-led RAMSI force in the Solomon Islands.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga is subdivided into five administrative divisions: ʻEua, Haʻapai, Niuas, Tongatapu, and Vavaʻu.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's economy is characterised by a large nonmonetary sector and a heavy dependence on remittances from the half of the country's population who live abroad (chiefly in Australia, New Zealand, and the United States).
[src:tonga/tonga] The royal family and the nobles dominate and largely own the monetary sector of the economy – particularly the telecommunications and satellite services.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga was named the sixth-most corrupt country in the world by *Forbes* magazine in 2008.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga was ranked the 165th-safest investment destination in the world in the March 2011 *Euromoney* Country Risk rankings.
[src:tonga/tonga] The manufacturing sector consists of handicrafts and a few other very small-scale industries, which contribute only about 5% of GDP.
[src:tonga/tonga] Commercial business activities also are inconspicuous, and to a large extent, are dominated by the same large trading companies found throughout the South Pacific.
[src:tonga/tonga] In September 1974, the country's first commercial trading bank, the Bank of Tonga, opened.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's development plans emphasise a growing private sector, upgrading agricultural productivity, revitalising the squash and vanilla-bean industries, developing tourism, and improving communications and transport.
[src:tonga/tonga] Substantial progress has been made, but much work remains to be done.
[src:tonga/tonga] A small, growing construction sector is developing in response to the inflow of aid money and remittances from Tongans abroad.
[src:tonga/tonga] In recognition of such a crucial contribution, the government has created a new department in the Prime Minister's Office with the purpose of catering for the needs of Tongans living abroad.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2007, the Tongan Parliament amended citizenship laws to allow Tongans to hold dual citizenship.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's postage stamps, featuring colourful and often unusual designs (including heart-shaped and banana-shaped stamps), are popular with philatelists.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2005, the country became eligible to become a member of the World Trade Organization.
[src:tonga/tonga] After an initial voluntary delay, Tonga became a full member of the WTO on 27 July 2007.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Tonga Chamber of Commerce and Industry, incorporated in 1996, endeavours to represent the interests of its members, private sector businesses, and to promote economic growth in the Kingdom.
[src:tonga/tonga] More than double that number live overseas, mainly in the US, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:tonga/tonga] Remittances from the overseas population have been declining since the onset of the 2008 global economic crisis.
[src:tonga/tonga] The tourism industry is improving, but remains modest at under 90,000 tourists per year.
[src:tonga/tonga] The tourist industry is relatively undeveloped.
[src:tonga/tonga] The government recognises that tourism can play a major role in economic development, and efforts are being made to increase this source of revenue.
[src:tonga/tonga] Cruise ships often stop in Vavaʻu, with a reputation for its whale watching, game fishing, surfing, beaches, and is increasingly becoming a major player in the South Pacific tourism market.
[src:tonga/tonga] In Tonga, agriculture and forestry (together with fisheries) provide the majority of employment, foreign exchange earnings, and food.
[src:tonga/tonga] Rural Tongans rely on both plantation and subsistence agriculture.
[src:tonga/tonga] Plants grown for both market cash crops and home use include bananas, coconuts, coffee beans, vanilla beans, and root crops such as cassava, sweet potato, and taro.
[src:tonga/tonga] As of 2001, two-thirds of agricultural land was in root crops.
[src:tonga/tonga] The processing of coconuts into copra and desiccated (dried) coconut was once the only significant industry, and only commercial export.
[src:tonga/tonga] Deteriorating prices on the world market and lack of replanting brought this once vibrant industry, as in most island nations of the South Pacific, to a complete standstill.
[src:tonga/tonga] Swine and poultry are the major types of livestock.
[src:tonga/tonga] Horses are kept for draft purposes, primarily by farmers working their*ʻapi ʻuta* (a plot of bushland); though the meat is also coveted.
[src:tonga/tonga] More cattle are being raised, and beef imports are declining.
[src:tonga/tonga] The traditional feudal land ownership system meant that farmers had no incentive to invest in planting long-term tree crops on land they did not own.
[src:tonga/tonga] In the late 20th century, kava and vanilla from larger plantations became the main agricultural exports, together with squash.
[src:tonga/tonga] The export of squash to Japan, beginning in 1987, once brought relief to Tonga's struggling economy, but local farmers became increasingly wary of the Japanese market due to price fluctuations, and the huge financial risks involved.
[src:tonga/tonga] Energy in Tonga mostly comes from imported diesel.
[src:tonga/tonga] Energy consumption in Tonga was projected to reach around 66 gigawatt hours by 2020.
[src:tonga/tonga] The country aimed to reach 50% of renewable energy by 2020.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2019, Tonga announced the construction of a 6-megawatt solar farm on Tongatapu.
[src:tonga/tonga] The plant will be the second-largest solar plant in the Pacific upon completion.
[src:tonga/tonga] In view of the decreasing reliability of fossil-fuel electricity generation, its increasing costs, and negative environmental side effects, renewable energy solutions have attracted the government's attention.
[src:tonga/tonga] Together with IRENA, Tonga has planned a renewable energy based strategy to power the main and outer islands.
[src:tonga/tonga] The strategy focuses on solar home systems that turn individual households into small power plants.
[src:tonga/tonga] It calls for the involvement of local operators, finance institutions, and technicians to provide sustainable business models and strategies to ensure the effective operation, management, and maintenance once the systems are installed.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Pacific Centre for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency was established in Tonga in 2016 to advise the private sector on related policy matters, provide capacity development and promote business investment.
[src:tonga/tonga] The centre facilitates a financial mechanism offering competitive grants for start-ups to spur the adoption of renewable energy by the business sector.
[src:tonga/tonga] The centre is part of the Global Network of Regional Sustainable Energy Centres and SIDS DOCK framework designed to attract international investment in the renewable energy sector.
[src:tonga/tonga] With the assistance of IRENA, Tonga has developed the 2010–2020 Tonga Energy Road Map, which aims for a 50% reduction of diesel importation.
[src:tonga/tonga] This was to be accomplished through a range of appropriate renewable technologies, including wind and solar, as well as innovative efficiencies.
[src:tonga/tonga] As of 2018, Tonga was generating 10% of its electricity from renewable sources.
[src:tonga/tonga] Over 70% of the 106,017 inhabitants live on its main island, Tongatapu.
[src:tonga/tonga] Although an increasing number of Tongans have moved into the only urban and commercial centre, Nukuʻalofa, where European and indigenous cultural and living patterns have blended, village life and kinship ties remain influential throughout the country.
[src:tonga/tonga] Despite emigration, Tonga grew in population from about 32,000 in the 1930s to more than 90,000 by 1976.
[src:tonga/tonga] According to the government portal, Tongans, Polynesian by ethnicity with a mixture of Melanesian, represent more than 98% of the inhabitants.
[src:tonga/tonga] About 1.5% are mixed Tongans and the rest are European (the majority are British), mixed European, and other Pacific Islanders.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2001, about 3,000 to 4,000 Chinese lived there, comprising 3 to 4% of the total Tongan population.
[src:tonga/tonga] The 2006 Nukuʻalofa riots mainly targeted Chinese-owned businesses, leading to the emigration of several hundred Chinese so that only about 300 remain.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tongan is the official language, along with English.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tongan is a Polynesian language of the Tongic branch, so it is closely related to other languages of the Tongic branch, those being: Niuean and Niuafoʻouan.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tongan is more distantly related to other Polynesian languages such as Hawaiian, Samoan, Māori, and Tahitian, among others.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga does not have an official state religion.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Constitution of Tonga (Revised 1998) provides for freedom of religion.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 1928, Queen Salote Tupou III, who was a member of the Free Wesleyan Church of Tonga, established the Free Wesleyan Church as the state religion of Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] The chief pastor of the Free Wesleyan Church serves as the representative of the people of Tonga and of the church at the coronation of a king or queen of Tonga, where he anoints and crowns the monarch.
[src:tonga/tonga] In opposition to the establishment of the Free Wesleyan Church as a state religion, the Church of Tonga separated from the Free Wesleyan Church in 1928.
[src:tonga/tonga] Islam in Tonga is a small minority religion in the country.
[src:tonga/tonga] Muslims in Tonga belong to Sunni denomination.
[src:tonga/tonga] Al-Khadeejah Mosque is a prominent mosque in Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Everyday life is heavily influenced by Polynesian traditions and by the Christian faith.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Sabbath is included in the constitution, with all commerce and entertainment activities stopped on Sundays.
[src:tonga/tonga] An estimated 18.6% were Mormons, 14.2% were Roman Catholic, and 2.4% followed other religions, while 0.5% followed no religion and 0.1% were of unspecified religious background.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints sent missionaries in 1891 to visit King Siaosi (George) Tupo, where they obtained permission to preach.
[src:tonga/tonga] By some published surveys, Tonga has one of the highest obesity rates in the world.
[src:tonga/tonga] World Health Organization data published in 2014 indicate that Tonga stands fourth overall in terms of countries listed by mean body mass index data.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2011, 90% of the adult population were considered overweight using NIH interpretation of body mass index (BMI) data, with more than 60% of those obese.
[src:tonga/tonga] 70% of Tongan females aged 15–85 are obese.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga and Nauru have the world's highest overweight and obese populations.
[src:tonga/tonga] In late October 2021, Tonga reported its first case of COVID-19 based on a New Zealand air passenger's positive test.
[src:tonga/tonga] Primary education between ages 6 and 14 is compulsory and free in state schools.
[src:tonga/tonga] Mission schools provide about 8% of the primary and 90% of the secondary level of education.
[src:tonga/tonga] Higher education includes teacher training, nursing, and medical training, a small private university, a woman's business college, and a number of private agricultural schools.
[src:tonga/tonga] Most levels of higher education are pursued overseas.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tongans enjoy a relatively high level of education, with a 98.9% literacy rate, and higher education up to and including medical and graduate degrees (pursued mostly overseas).
[src:tonga/tonga] They hold the body of academic knowledge created by their scholars in high esteem and the Kukū Kaunaka Collection, which comprises every doctoral and master's dissertation written by any Tongan in any country, is archived by Seu'ula Johansson-Fua at the Institute for Education in Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Contemporary Tongans often have strong ties to overseas lands.
[src:tonga/tonga] Many Tongans have emigrated to Australia, New Zealand, or the United States to seek employment and a higher standard of living.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2018, 82,389 Tongans lived in New Zealand.
[src:tonga/tonga] As of 2000, 36,840 Tongans were living in the US.
[src:tonga/tonga] More than 8,000 Tongans live in Australia.
[src:tonga/tonga] The Tongan diaspora retains close ties to relatives at home, and a significant portion of Tonga's income derives from remittances to family members (often aged) who prefer to remain in Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Humans have lived in Tonga for nearly 3,000 years since settlement in late Lapita times.
[src:tonga/tonga] Before the arrival of European explorers in the late 17th and early 18th centuries, Tongans had frequent contacts with their nearest Oceanic neighbours, Fiji and Niue.
[src:tonga/tonga] In the 19th century, with the arrival of Western traders and missionaries, Tongan culture changed, especially in religion.
[src:tonga/tonga] As of 2013, almost 98% of residents profess Christianity.
[src:tonga/tonga] The people discarded some old beliefs and habits and adopted others.
[src:tonga/tonga] Fahu is a form of social organization practiced by the people of Tonga, built upon a relationship between a person and their father's sister and paternal cousins.
[src:tonga/tonga] Prior to Western contact, the inner dynamics between the chiefly kinship groups were governed by this social convention.
[src:tonga/tonga] Although fahu rights do not hold the same political strength and implications they historically did, they remain, to a notable degree, a part of the contemporary social practices in Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] Similar social structures to fahu have been cited as significantly beneficial for human adaptation to environmental threats, especially those situated in hurricane-prone regions such as Tonga.
[src:tonga/tonga] The benefit stems from the fahu's ability to provide a network and capacity to allow for relocation of people and resources during environmental events, such as hurricanes or droughts.
[src:tonga/tonga] However, there have been environmental consequences of note due to the fahu structure, or rather, a disturbance of the structure.
[src:tonga/tonga] In the 1980s, Tonga saw a severe depletion of its sandalwood tree due to a disruption of the fahu social hierarchy, which was incited by market demand for the resource.
[src:tonga/tonga] This led to heightened local competition and eventually an overharvest of the tree.
[src:tonga/tonga] Nearly all of the sandalwood resources were depleted over the span of two years.
[src:tonga/tonga] Rugby union is the national sport, and the national team (ʻIkale Tahi, or Sea Eagles) has succeeded internationally.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga has competed in six Rugby World Cups since 1987.
[src:tonga/tonga] The 2007 and 2011 Rugby World Cups were Tonga's most successful to date, both winning two out of four matches and in a running chance for the quarterfinals.
[src:tonga/tonga] In the 2007 Rugby World Cup, Tonga won its first two matches, against the USA 25–15, and Samoa 19–15.
[src:tonga/tonga] They came very close to upsetting the eventual winners of the 2007 tournament, the South African Springboks, losing 30–25.
[src:tonga/tonga] A defeat by England, 36–20 in their last pool game ended their hopes of making the knockout stages.
[src:tonga/tonga] Nevertheless, by picking up third place in their pool games behind South Africa and England, Tonga earned automatic qualification for the 2011 Rugby World Cup in New Zealand.
[src:tonga/tonga] In Pool A of the 2011 Rugby World Cup, Tonga beat both Japan 31–18 and 5th ranked eventual finalist France 19–14 in the latter pool stages.
[src:tonga/tonga] However, a previous heavy defeat by the All Blacks at the tournament's opener (41–10) and a subsequent tight defeat by Canada (25–20) meant that Tonga lost out to France (who also lost to NZ) for the quarter finals due to 2 bonus points and a points difference of 46.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's best result before 2007 came in 1995, when they beat Côte d'Ivoire 29–11, and 1999 when they beat Italy 28–25 (although with only 14 men they lost heavily to England, 101–10).
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga perform the Ikale Tahi war dance or Sipi Tau (a form of Kailao) before all their matches.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga used to compete in the Pacific Tri-Nations against Samoa and Fiji, which has now been replaced by the World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup, which now involves Japan, Canada, and the United States.
[src:tonga/tonga] At club level, there are the Datec Cup Provincial Championship and the Pacific Rugby Cup.
[src:tonga/tonga] Rugby union is governed by the Tonga Rugby Football Union, which was a member of the Pacific Islands Rugby Alliance and contributed to the Pacific Islanders rugby union team, before they were disbanded in 2009.
[src:tonga/tonga] British and Irish Lion and Welsh international player Taulupe "Toby" Faletau is Tongan born and the son of Tongan international Kuli Faletau.
[src:tonga/tonga] Taulupe's cousins and England international players Billy and Mako Vunipola (who is also a British and Irish Lion), are sons of former Tonga rugby captain Fe'ao Vunipola.
[src:tonga/tonga] Rugby is popular among the nation's schools, and students from schools such as Tonga College and Tupou College are regularly offered scholarships in New Zealand, Australia and Japan.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga made their first appearance at a Rugby League World Cup in the 1995 edition where they went out in the first stage but narrowly lost to New Zealand.
[src:tonga/tonga] They have since appeared in each subsequent Rugby League World Cup tournament.
[src:tonga/tonga] In the 2008 Rugby League World Cup Tonga recorded wins against Ireland and Scotland.
[src:tonga/tonga] Just before the 2017 World Cup, various high-profile players, led by Jason Taumalolo and Andrew Fifita, defected from their tier one nations to represent their nation of heritage.
[src:tonga/tonga] This led to them defeating New Zealand in Hamilton at Waikato Stadium on 11 November at that tournament.
[src:tonga/tonga] The national team has since also recorded victories against Great Britain and the world number one Australia.
[src:tonga/tonga] In addition to the success of the national team, many players of Tongan descent make it big in the Australian National Rugby League competition.
[src:tonga/tonga] Subsequently, some Tongan rugby league players have established successful careers in the Super League such as Antonio Kaufusi.
[src:tonga/tonga] Aside from rugby, Tonga has also produced athletes who have competed at both the Summer and Winter Olympics.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tonga's only Olympic medal came from the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta, where Paea Wolfgramm won silver in super heavyweight boxing.
[src:tonga/tonga] One athlete, Pita Taufatofua, attended the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang, South Korea.
[src:tonga/tonga] There has been a huge surge of contemporary Tongan artists in the past decade, the majority based in New Zealand.
[src:tonga/tonga] Tanya Edwards works with ngatu (bark cloths), Benjamin Work, Telly Tuita, and Sione Monū are widely exhibited internationally, Sēmisi Fetokai Potauaine built a five-storey Tongan sculpture in central Christchurch.
[src:tonga/tonga] In 2023, Bergman Gallery hosted *Tukufakaholo, Tongan Contemporary* in Auckland, New Zealand, featuring eight Tongan artists.
